"catalyst\": \"magnetite and greigite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"alkaline vent gradients, anoxic\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Sequential C1 fixation and reductive carboxylation on mineral surfaces produces alpha-keto acid pools including pyruvate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Mineral-promoted fixation networks in hydrothermal settings have been proposed to access pyruvate and related alpha-keto acids from CO2 and H2 under vent conditions (Muchowska et al., 2019; Moran et al., 2020).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_004\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface photochemical generation of HCN from reduced carbon pools\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_004\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"TiO2 and sulfide minerals\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"UV irradiation, evaporitic concentration, anoxic\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Photoredox and dehydration chemistry of reduced C1-N species generates cyanide under UV-exposed surface conditions.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"HCN is central to cyanosulfidic prebiotic chemistry and can arise in UV-driven reduced atmospheric or surface photochemical settings; this step is used as a surface entry node consistent with cyanosulfidic frameworks though the exact formaldehyde-to-HCN conversion is a network simplification (Patel et al., 2015; Ritson & Sutherland, 2012).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_005\",\n      \"name\": \"Borate-stabilized aldol formation of glycolaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_007\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)\", \"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"borate minerals\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"wet-dry cycling and UV-assisted carbonyl chemistry\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Reduced C1 carbonyl species undergo coupling to yield C2 aldehydes, with borate stabilizing reactive oxygenated products.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Glycolaldehyde and other simple sugars can arise from formose-like and photoredox chemistry, and borate minerals stabilize oxygenated intermediates in surface settings (Ricardo et al., 2004; Ritson & Sutherland, 2012).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_006\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface convergent pyruvate formation from glycolaldehyde and formate pools\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_005\", \"mol_015\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_008\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)\", \"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"320-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"borate and phosphate minerals\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"evaporitic concentration, aldol/carboxylation network\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Surface carbonyl coupling and carboxylation generate alpha-keto acid products, converging on pyruvate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Alpha-keto acids can emerge from prebiotic carbonyl network chemistry linking formose-type intermediates and carboxylation steps; direct pyruvate formation in such systems remains partly speculative but is used to create a chemically plausible convergence with hydrothermal routes (Weber, 2001; Muchowska et al., 2020).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_007\",\n      \"name\": \"Strecker-type synthesis of 2-aminobutyrate from pyruvate/cyanide network\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_009\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite (clay)\", \"sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite and sulfide minerals\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"evaporitic pools, aminonitrile formation followed by hydrolysis\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Carbonyl addition of cyanide and ammonia forms an aminonitrile that hydrolyzes to an amino acid product, represented here as a C4 amino-acid pool feeding downstream carbon skeleton rearrangements.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Strecker chemistry is strongly supported for prebiotic amino acid synthesis from aldehydes/ketones, NH3, and HCN. The exact assignment to a specific C4 amino acid in this network is a simplifying carbon-skeleton placeholder linking pyruvate/cyanide chemistry to proline precursors (Miller, 1957; Parker et al., 2011).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_008\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface dehydration to unsaturated C4 acid\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_009\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_010\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite (clay)\", \"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"330-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"false\",\n        \"other\": \"wet-dry cycles, dehydration-favored\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Drying-driven elimination and rearrangement convert hydroxy/amino acid pools into unsaturated carboxylate intermediates.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Wet-dry cycles on mineral surfaces promote dehydration and rearrangement reactions that are otherwise unfavorable in dilute aqueous solution; this step is more speculative but provides a plausible route to reactive C4 scaffolds for later C5 amino acid formation (Forsythe et al., 2015).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_009\",\n      \"name\": \"Biochemical-like homologation and transamination to glutamate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [\"mineral interfaces\", \"Fe2+\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-360K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"mineral interfaces and dissolved ferrous iron\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"prebiotic pools, repeated heating/cooling\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Carbon-skeleton extension and amination/transamination convert keto-acid and unsaturated-acid pools into glutamate-like amino acid products.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Glutamate is a plausible prebiotic amino donor/acceptor hub in protometabolic networks. This exact homologation is speculative, but alpha-keto acid amination and network-level carbon rearrangements are consistent with prebiotic protometabolism proposals (Muchowska et al., 2019; Kitadai et al., 2018).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_010\",\n      \"name\": \"Reduction of glutamate to glutamate-semialdehyde equivalent\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_012\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [\"mineral interfaces\", \"Fe2+\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"iron-rich mineral surfaces\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"reducing microenvironments in protocell or mineral compartments\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Partial reduction of a terminal carboxylate functionality gives a semialdehyde equivalent capable of intramolecular cyclization.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"In biology, glutamate is reduced to glutamate semialdehyde en route to proline. Prebiotically, analogous partial reductions on metal-rich surfaces are plausible but not firmly established, so this is a necessary speculative bridge grounded in known redox behavior of carboxylates in reducing mineral systems (Huber & Wachtershauser, 1997; Muchowska et al., 2020).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_011\",\n      \"name\": \"Cyclization and reduction to L-proline\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_012\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_013\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [\"mineral interfaces\", \"geothermal cycling\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"none required beyond mineral confinement\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"intramolecular Schiff-base-like cyclization, wet-dry/geothermal cycles\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"The amino aldehyde equivalent spontaneously cyclizes to a pyrroline-like ring which is subsequently reduced to pyrrolidine-2-carboxylate, yielding proline.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Cyclization of glutamate-semialdehyde to a five-membered ring is chemically favorable and mirrors the known biosynthetic logic of proline formation. The final reduction is prebiotically plausible in reducing compartments, although stereoselective enrichment to the L-form would likely require selection processes rather than a single reaction event (Leman et al., 2004; Islam et al., 2017).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_012\",\n      \"name\": \"HCN hydration to formamide as auxiliary cyanide reservoir\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_014\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"montmorillonite (clay)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"TiO2\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"UV-exposed ponds, concentration by evaporation\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Hydration and photochemical stabilization convert HCN into formamide, a reservoir and transfer intermediate for N-containing chemistry.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Formamide is a commonly invoked prebiotic intermediate derived from HCN-containing chemistry and participates in broader nucleotide and amino acid precursor networks under mineral-assisted heating and irradiation (Saladino et al., 2012).\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"Direct hydrothermal pyruvate to proline route\",\n      \"description\": \"CO2 is reduced hydrothermally to formate and then to pyruvate, which is elaborated biochemically through glutamate and glutamate-semialdehyde to proline.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_012\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P2\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal C1 to HCN-assisted route\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal formaldehyde feeds surface HCN production, which then joins pyruvate chemistry before biochemical closure to proline.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_011\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P3\",\n      \"name\": \"Formate-formaldehyde-glycolaldehyde surface convergence\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal formate and formaldehyde are transferred to surface pools where glycolaldehyde and then pyruvate are formed prior to biochemical conversion to proline.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_006\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_008\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P4\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal pyruvate plus surface cyanide diversification\",\n      \"description\": \"Pyruvate produced hydrothermally is exported to surface environments for Strecker-type chemistry, then the resulting C4 intermediate is routed back into biochemical proline synthesis.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_010\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P5\",\n      \"name\": \"Formamide-buffered cyanide pathway\",\n      \"description\": \"Surface cyanide generated from hydrothermal C1 carbon is buffered through formamide chemistry before re-entering the amino-acid precursor network leading to proline.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_014\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_011\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P6\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface pyruvate convergence from glycolaldehyde\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal one-carbon products are transformed on the surface into glycolaldehyde and then into pyruvate, bypassing direct hydrothermal pyruvate dependence.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_010\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P7\",\n      \"name\": \"Dual-convergence formate and pyruvate route\",\n      \"description\": \"Formate serves both as a hydrothermal reduction product and as a surface carbonyl-coupling partner, creating a redundant network that converges on pyruvate before proline assembly.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_006\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_008\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P8\",\n      \"name\": \"HCN-first then pyruvate-assisted glutamate route\",\n      \"description\": \"A strong cyanide pool is built from hydrothermal C1 species, then joins pyruvate in surface chemistry to furnish amino-acid precursors that mature to glutamate and proline.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_011\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P9\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal-to-surface-to-biochemical closed loop\",\n      \"description\": \"Products from vents feed surface carbonyl and cyanide chemistry, and those products in turn generate a glutamate hub in concentrated pools that closes to proline.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_011\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P10\",\n      \"name\": \"Maximum redundancy multi-hub route\",\n      \"description\": \"This route explicitly traverses the major hubs formate, formaldehyde, HCN, glycolaldehyde, pyruvate, glutamate, and glutamate-semialdehyde before arriving at proline.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_006\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_012\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"hub_molecules\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_005\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_012\"],\n  \"convergence_points\": [\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_005\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_001\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_008\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_006\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_007\", \"rxn_009\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_004\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_004\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_007\", \"rxn_012\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_011\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_009\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_010\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_012\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_010\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_011\"]\n    }\n  ]\n}", "parsed_response": {"target_molecule": "L-Proline", "overall_strategy": "The network targets L-proline through convergent prebiotic production of shared hubs including formate, formaldehyde, hydrogen cyanide, pyruvate, and glutamate-semialdehyde equivalents, with hydrothermal carbon fixation and iron-sulfur chemistry feeding surface cyanide, sugar, and aminonitrile chemistry, followed by biochemical transamination, cyclization, and reduction to proline. Ten distinct pathways are represented as alternative routes that converge on hub intermediates and then diverge into hydrothermal, surface, and biochemical completion routes.", "molecules": [{"id": "mol_001", "formula": "CO2", "iupac_name": "carbon dioxide", "common_name": "carbon dioxide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_002", "formula": "H2", "iupac_name": "molecular hydrogen", "common_name": "hydrogen", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2/h1H", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_003", "formula": "NH3", "iupac_name": "azane", "common_name": "ammonia", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_004", "formula": "HCN", "iupac_name": "hydrogen cyanide", "common_name": "hydrogen cyanide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_005", "formula": "CH2O2", "iupac_name": "methanoic acid", "common_name": "formic acid/formate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH2O2/c2-1-3/h1H,(H,2,3)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_006", "formula": "CH2O", "iupac_name": "methanal", "common_name": "formaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH2O/c1-2/h1H2", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_007", "formula": "C2H4O2", "iupac_name": "2-hydroxyethanal", "common_name": "glycolaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H4O2/c3-1-2-4/h1,3H,2H2", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_008", "formula": "C3H6O3", "iupac_name": "2-oxopropanoic acid", "common_name": "pyruvic acid/pyruvate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H4O3/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h1H3,(H,5,6)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_009", "formula": "C4H7NO2", "iupac_name": "2-aminobutanoic acid", "common_name": "2-aminobutyrate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C4H9NO2/c1-2-3(5)4(6)7/h3H,2,5H2,1H3,(H,6,7)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_010", "formula": "C4H6O2", "iupac_name": "but-2-enoic acid", "common_name": "crotonic acid", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C4H6O2/c1-2-3-4(5)6/h2-3H,1H3,(H,5,6)/b3-2+", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_011", "formula": "C5H7NO4", "iupac_name": "2-aminopentanedioic acid", "common_name": "glutamic acid/glutamate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H9NO4/c6-3(5(9)10)1-2-4(7)8/h3H,1-2,6H2,(H,7,8)(H,9,10)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_012", "formula": "C5H7NO2", "iupac_name": "5-amino-2-oxopentanoic acid", "common_name": "glutamate semialdehyde equivalent", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H9NO3/c6-3-1-2-4(7)5(8)9/h4H,1-3,6H2,(H,8,9)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_013", "formula": "C5H9NO2", "iupac_name": "pyrrolidine-2-carboxylic acid", "common_name": "L-proline", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H9NO2/c7-5(8)4-2-1-3-6-4/h4,6H,1-3H2,(H,7,8)/t4-/m0/s1", "role": "target", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_014", "formula": "CHNO", "iupac_name": "methanamide", "common_name": "formamide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH3NO/c2-1-3/h1H,(H2,2,3)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_015", "formula": "H3PO4", "iupac_name": "phosphoric acid", "common_name": "phosphate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H3O4P/c1-5(2,3)4/h(H3,1,2,3,4)", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}], "reactions": [{"id": "rxn_001", "name": "Greigite-catalyzed CO2 reduction to formate", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_005"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite (Fe3S4)", "mackinawite (FeS)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "greigite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "alkaline vent conditions, anoxic, H2-rich"}, "mechanism": "Mineral-surface electron transfer reduces CO2 with H2 to formate on iron-sulfur surfaces.", "reasoning": "Iron-sulfur minerals such as greigite and mackinawite are widely used as analogs for hydrothermal CO2 reduction and acetyl-CoA-pathway-like chemistry in alkaline vent scenarios (Huber & Wachtershauser, 1997; Roldan et al., 2015)."}, {"id": "rxn_002", "name": "Magnetite/iron reduction of CO2-derived carbon to formaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_005", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_006"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite (Fe3O4)", "elemental iron (Fe0)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "370-450K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "magnetite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "subseafloor reducing conditions"}, "mechanism": "Further reduction of one-carbon species on metal oxide/metal surfaces yields reduced carbonyl products including formaldehyde-like carbonyl pools.", "reasoning": "Reduced hydrothermal systems with magnetite and Fe0 support CO2 hydrogenation and Fischer-Tropsch-type chemistry generating reduced C1 species, though direct formaldehyde accumulation is context-dependent and partly speculative for network continuity (McCollom & Seewald, 2007; He et al., 2010)."}, {"id": "rxn_003", "name": "Hydrothermal synthesis of pyruvate from reduced carbon", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002", "mol_005"], "outputs": ["mol_008"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite (Fe3O4)", "greigite (Fe3S4)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "magnetite and greigite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "alkaline vent gradients, anoxic"}, "mechanism": "Sequential C1 fixation and reductive carboxylation on mineral surfaces produces alpha-keto acid pools including pyruvate.", "reasoning": "Mineral-promoted fixation networks in hydrothermal settings have been proposed to access pyruvate and related alpha-keto acids from CO2 and H2 under vent conditions (Muchowska et al., 2019; Moran et al., 2020)."}, {"id": "rxn_004", "name": "Surface photochemical generation of HCN from reduced carbon pools", "inputs": ["mol_006", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_004"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-340K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "TiO2 and sulfide minerals", "aqueous": "true", "other": "UV irradiation, evaporitic concentration, anoxic"}, "mechanism": "Photoredox and dehydration chemistry of reduced C1-N species generates cyanide under UV-exposed surface conditions.", "reasoning": "HCN is central to cyanosulfidic prebiotic chemistry and can arise in UV-driven reduced atmospheric or surface photochemical settings; this step is used as a surface entry node consistent with cyanosulfidic frameworks though the exact formaldehyde-to-HCN conversion is a network simplification (Patel et al., 2015; Ritson & Sutherland, 2012)."}, {"id": "rxn_005", "name": "Borate-stabilized aldol formation of glycolaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_006", "mol_005"], "outputs": ["mol_007"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)", "TiO2 (anatase/rutile)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "borate minerals", "aqueous": "true", "other": "wet-dry cycling and UV-assisted carbonyl chemistry"}, "mechanism": "Reduced C1 carbonyl species undergo coupling to yield C2 aldehydes, with borate stabilizing reactive oxygenated products.", "reasoning": "Glycolaldehyde and other simple sugars can arise from formose-like and photoredox chemistry, and borate minerals stabilize oxygenated intermediates in surface settings (Ricardo et al., 2004; Ritson & Sutherland, 2012)."}, {"id": "rxn_006", "name": "Surface convergent pyruvate formation from glycolaldehyde and formate pools", "inputs": ["mol_007", "mol_005", "mol_015"], "outputs": ["mol_008"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)", "phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "320-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "borate and phosphate minerals", "aqueous": "true", "other": "evaporitic concentration, aldol/carboxylation network"}, "mechanism": "Surface carbonyl coupling and carboxylation generate alpha-keto acid products, converging on pyruvate.", "reasoning": "Alpha-keto acids can emerge from prebiotic carbonyl network chemistry linking formose-type intermediates and carboxylation steps; direct pyruvate formation in such systems remains partly speculative but is used to create a chemically plausible convergence with hydrothermal routes (Weber, 2001; Muchowska et al., 2020)."}, {"id": "rxn_007", "name": "Strecker-type synthesis of 2-aminobutyrate from pyruvate/cyanide network", "inputs": ["mol_008", "mol_004", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_009"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite (clay)", "sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite and sulfide minerals", "aqueous": "true", "other": "evaporitic pools, aminonitrile formation followed by hydrolysis"}, "mechanism": "Carbonyl addition of cyanide and ammonia forms an aminonitrile that hydrolyzes to an amino acid product, represented here as a C4 amino-acid pool feeding downstream carbon skeleton rearrangements.", "reasoning": "Strecker chemistry is strongly supported for prebiotic amino acid synthesis from aldehydes/ketones, NH3, and HCN. The exact assignment to a specific C4 amino acid in this network is a simplifying carbon-skeleton placeholder linking pyruvate/cyanide chemistry to proline precursors (Miller, 1957; Parker et al., 2011)."}, {"id": "rxn_008", "name": "Surface dehydration to unsaturated C4 acid", "inputs": ["mol_009"], "outputs": ["mol_010"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite (clay)", "phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "330-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite", "aqueous": "false", "other": "wet-dry cycles, dehydration-favored"}, "mechanism": "Drying-driven elimination and rearrangement convert hydroxy/amino acid pools into unsaturated carboxylate intermediates.", "reasoning": "Wet-dry cycles on mineral surfaces promote dehydration and rearrangement reactions that are otherwise unfavorable in dilute aqueous solution; this step is more speculative but provides a plausible route to reactive C4 scaffolds for later C5 amino acid formation (Forsythe et al., 2015)."}, {"id": "rxn_009", "name": "Biochemical-like homologation and transamination to glutamate", "inputs": ["mol_008", "mol_010", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_011"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": ["mineral interfaces", "Fe2+"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-360K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "mineral interfaces and dissolved ferrous iron", "aqueous": "true", "other": "prebiotic pools, repeated heating/cooling"}, "mechanism": "Carbon-skeleton extension and amination/transamination convert keto-acid and unsaturated-acid pools into glutamate-like amino acid products.", "reasoning": "Glutamate is a plausible prebiotic amino donor/acceptor hub in protometabolic networks. This exact homologation is speculative, but alpha-keto acid amination and network-level carbon rearrangements are consistent with prebiotic protometabolism proposals (Muchowska et al., 2019; Kitadai et al., 2018)."}, {"id": "rxn_010", "name": "Reduction of glutamate to glutamate-semialdehyde equivalent", "inputs": ["mol_011", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_012"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": ["mineral interfaces", "Fe2+"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "iron-rich mineral surfaces", "aqueous": "true", "other": "reducing microenvironments in protocell or mineral compartments"}, "mechanism": "Partial reduction of a terminal carboxylate functionality gives a semialdehyde equivalent capable of intramolecular cyclization.", "reasoning": "In biology, glutamate is reduced to glutamate semialdehyde en route to proline. Prebiotically, analogous partial reductions on metal-rich surfaces are plausible but not firmly established, so this is a necessary speculative bridge grounded in known redox behavior of carboxylates in reducing mineral systems (Huber & Wachtershauser, 1997; Muchowska et al., 2020)."}, {"id": "rxn_011", "name": "Cyclization and reduction to L-proline", "inputs": ["mol_012", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_013"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": ["mineral interfaces", "geothermal cycling"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "none required beyond mineral confinement", "aqueous": "true", "other": "intramolecular Schiff-base-like cyclization, wet-dry/geothermal cycles"}, "mechanism": "The amino aldehyde equivalent spontaneously cyclizes to a pyrroline-like ring which is subsequently reduced to pyrrolidine-2-carboxylate, yielding proline.", "reasoning": "Cyclization of glutamate-semialdehyde to a five-membered ring is chemically favorable and mirrors the known biosynthetic logic of proline formation. The final reduction is prebiotically plausible in reducing compartments, although stereoselective enrichment to the L-form would likely require selection processes rather than a single reaction event (Leman et al., 2004; Islam et al., 2017)."}, {"id": "rxn_012", "name": "HCN hydration to formamide as auxiliary cyanide reservoir", "inputs": ["mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_014"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "montmorillonite (clay)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "TiO2", "aqueous": "true", "other": "UV-exposed ponds, concentration by evaporation"}, "mechanism": "Hydration and photochemical stabilization convert HCN into formamide, a reservoir and transfer intermediate for N-containing chemistry.", "reasoning": "Formamide is a commonly invoked prebiotic intermediate derived from HCN-containing chemistry and participates in broader nucleotide and amino acid precursor networks under mineral-assisted heating and irradiation (Saladino et al., 2012)."}], "pathways": [{"pathway_id": "P1", "name": "Direct hydrothermal pyruvate to proline route", "description": "CO2 is reduced hydrothermally to formate and then to pyruvate, which is elaborated biochemically through glutamate and glutamate-semialdehyde to proline.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_003", "rxn_009", "rxn_010", "rxn_011"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_005", "mol_008", "mol_011", "mol_012"]}, {"pathway_id": "P2", "name": "Hydrothermal C1 to HCN-assisted route", "description": "Hydrothermal formaldehyde feeds surface HCN production, which then joins pyruvate chemistry before biochemical closure to proline.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_002", "rxn_004", "rxn_007", "rxn_008", "rxn_009", "rxn_010", "rxn_011"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_006", "mol_004", "mol_009", "mol_010", "mol_011"]}, {"pathway_id": "P3", "name": "Formate-formaldehyde-glycolaldehyde surface convergence", "description": "Hydrothermal formate and formaldehyde are transferred to surface pools where glycolaldehyde and then pyruvate are formed prior to biochemical conversion to proline.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_002", "rxn_005", "rxn_006", "rxn_009", "rxn_010", "rxn_011"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_005", "mol_006", "mol_007", "mol_008"]}, {"pathway_id": "P4", "name": "Hydrothermal pyruvate plus surface cyanide diversification", "description": "Pyruvate produced hydrothermally is exported to surface environments for Strecker-type chemistry, then the resulting C4 intermediate is routed back into biochemical proline synthesis.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_003", "rxn_004", "rxn_007", "rxn_008", "rxn_009", "rxn_010", "rxn_011"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_008", "mol_004", "mol_009", "mol_010"]}, {"pathway_id": "P5", "name": "Formamide-buffered cyanide pathway", "description": "Surface cyanide generated from hydrothermal C1 carbon is buffered through formamide chemistry before re-entering the amino-acid precursor network leading to proline.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_002", "rxn_004", "rxn_012", "rxn_007", "rxn_008", "rxn_009", "rxn_010", "rxn_011"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_004", "mol_014", "mol_009", "mol_011"]}, {"pathway_id": "P6", "name": "Surface pyruvate convergence from glycolaldehyde", "description": "Hydrothermal one-carbon products are transformed on the surface into glycolaldehyde and then into pyruvate, bypassing direct hydrothermal pyruvate dependence.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_002", "rxn_005", "rxn_006", "rxn_007", "rxn_008", "rxn_009", "rxn_010", "rxn_011"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_007", "mol_008", "mol_009", "mol_010"]}, {"pathway_id": "P7", "name": "Dual-convergence formate and pyruvate route", "description": "Formate serves both as a hydrothermal reduction product and as a surface carbonyl-coupling partner, creating a redundant network that converges on pyruvate before proline assembly.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_003", "rxn_002", "rxn_005", "rxn_006", "rxn_009", "rxn_010", "rxn_011"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_005", "mol_006", "mol_007", "mol_008"]}, {"pathway_id": "P8", "name": "HCN-first then pyruvate-assisted glutamate route", "description": "A strong cyanide pool is built from hydrothermal C1 species, then joins pyruvate in surface chemistry to furnish amino-acid precursors that mature to glutamate and proline.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_002", "rxn_004", "rxn_003", "rxn_007", "rxn_009", "rxn_010", "rxn_011"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_004", "mol_008", "mol_009", "mol_011"]}, {"pathway_id": "P9", "name": "Hydrothermal-to-surface-to-biochemical closed loop", "description": "Products from vents feed surface carbonyl and cyanide chemistry, and those products in turn generate a glutamate hub in concentrated pools that closes to proline.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_002", "rxn_005", "rxn_006", "rxn_004", "rxn_007", "rxn_009", "rxn_010", "rxn_011"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_006", "mol_007", "mol_004", "mol_011"]}, {"pathway_id": "P10", "name": "Maximum redundancy multi-hub route", "description": "This route explicitly traverses the major hubs formate, formaldehyde, HCN, glycolaldehyde, pyruvate, glutamate, and glutamate-semialdehyde before arriving at proline.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_002", "rxn_004", "rxn_005", "rxn_006", "rxn_007", "rxn_008", "rxn_009", "rxn_010", "rxn_011"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_005", "mol_006", "mol_004", "mol_007", "mol_008", "mol_011", "mol_012"]}], "hub_molecules": ["mol_004", "mol_005", "mol_008", "mol_011", "mol_012"], "convergence_points": [{"molecule_id": "mol_005", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_001"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_002", "rxn_003", "rxn_005", "rxn_006"]}, {"molecule_id": "mol_008", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_003", "rxn_006"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_007", "rxn_009"]}, {"molecule_id": "mol_004", "inco