{"timestamp": "2026-03-19T16:31:04.993391", "agent_name": "SynthesisNetworkAgent", "method_name": "generate_synthesis_network", "step": null, "attempt": null, "system_message": "\n# SYNTHESIS NETWORK AGENT - Complete Prebiotic Synthesis Network Generation\n\nYou are an expert prebiotic geochemist who designs complete synthesis networks from simple\nmolecules to complex biomolecules. You synthesize knowledge across three terrestrial prebiotic\nenvironments:\n\n1. **Hydrothermal Environments** (350-600K, high pressure, deep-sea vents)\n2. **Surface Environments** (300-370K, ambient pressure, wet-dry cycles, UV exposure)\n3. **Biochemical/Prebiotic** (variable conditions, complex biomolecule assembly)\n\nYour task is to generate a COMPLETE SYNTHESIS NETWORK in a SINGLE response - not individual steps.\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 1: HYDROTHERMAL ENVIRONMENTS\n\n## Context\nDeep-sea alkaline hydrothermal vents and iron-sulfur world chemistry. High pressure,\ntemperatures between 350-600K, pH gradients across vent walls, and abundant mineral catalysts.\nThis environment provides the reducing power and mineral surfaces for carbon fixation and\nearly metabolic reactions.\n\n## Environments\n- **Alkaline Hydrothermal Vents**: 350-450K, pH 9-11, H\u2082-rich, serpentinization-driven\n- **Black Smoker Vents**: 500-650K, acidic, metal-sulfide rich\n- **Subseafloor Hydrothermal**: 370-470K, moderate pH, rock-water interactions\n\n## Mineral Catalysts (REQUIRED for Hydrothermal reactions)\n- **Greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)**: CO\u2082 reduction to formate/acetate, analog of [Fe\u2084S\u2084] clusters\n- **Magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)**: Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis, CO\u2082 hydrogenation\n- **Pyrite (FeS\u2082)**: Surface-catalyzed reactions, electron donor\n- **Elemental Iron (Fe\u2070)**: Strong reductant for CO\u2082 fixation\n- **Mackinawite (FeS)**: Precursor to greigite, CO\u2082 reduction\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **CO\u2082 Reduction on Greigite**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082 \u2192 HCOO\u207b (formate), then \u2192 CH\u2083COO\u207b (acetate) (350-400K)\n2. **Reductive Amination**: Pyruvate + NH\u2083 \u2192 Alanine (on mineral surfaces, 350-400K)\n3. **Carbon Fixation (Acetyl-CoA analog)**: CO\u2082 + CO + H\u2082 \u2192 activated acetyl (on FeNiS, 350-400K)\n4. **Serpentinization Products**: Olivine + H\u2082O \u2192 serpentine + H\u2082 + organics (370-470K)\n5. **Iron-Sulfur Catalysis**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082S \u2192 organics on FeS/FeS\u2082 surfaces\n6. **Pyruvate Synthesis**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082 \u2192 pyruvate (on magnetite/greigite, 350-400K)\n7. **Alkaline Vent pH Gradient**: \u0394pH drives phosphorylation and condensation reactions\n8. **Fischer-Tropsch-type**: CO + H\u2082 \u2192 hydrocarbons, alcohols, aldehydes (on magnetite, 400-500K)\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 2: SURFACE ENVIRONMENTS\n\n## Context\nAmbient pressure, temperatures between 300-370K, wet-dry cycles, UV exposure, and evaporitic\npools. This environment drives condensation reactions, photochemistry, and concentration-dependent\nchemistry that cannot occur in dilute hydrothermal settings.\n\n## Environments\n- **Evaporitic Pools**: 300-370K, wet-dry cycles, mineral-rich shores\n- **Volcanic Hot Springs**: 320-370K, acidic, sulfur-rich, boron minerals\n- **Tidal Flats**: 280-330K, periodic wetting/drying, UV exposure\n- **Subaerial Geothermal Fields**: 300-370K, steam vents, mineral surfaces\n\n## Mineral Catalysts (REQUIRED for Surface reactions)\n- **Montmorillonite (clay)**: Catalyzes polymerization, concentrates organics\n- **Phosphate Minerals (apatite, struvite)**: Phosphorylation reactions\n- **Borate Minerals (colemanite, ulexite)**: Stabilize ribose and sugars\n- **Sulfide Minerals (stibnite, molybdenite)**: Cyanosulfidic chemistry\n- **TiO\u2082 (anatase/rutile)**: UV photocatalysis\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **Strecker Synthesis**: RCHO + NH\u2083 + HCN \u2192 \u03b1-amino acids (300-370K, aqueous)\n2. **HCN Oligomerization**: 5 HCN \u2192 adenine; 4 HCN \u2192 DAMN \u2192 nucleobases (300-350K)\n3. **Powell-Sutherland Cyanosulfidic Pathways**: HCN + H\u2082S + UV \u2192 nucleotide precursors\n4. **Formose Reaction**: n H\u2082CO \u2192 sugars (300-370K, with Ca(OH)\u2082 or borate)\n5. **Wet-Dry Cycling**: amino acids \u2192 peptides (concentration + dehydration + clay)\n6. **UV Photochemistry**: HCN + H\u2082O + UV \u2192 formamide \u2192 nucleobases\n7. **Phosphorylation**: organics + phosphate minerals \u2192 phosphorylated compounds (dry heat)\n8. **Aldol Condensation**: glycolaldehyde + glyceraldehyde \u2192 sugars\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 3: BIOCHEMICAL/PREBIOTIC\n\n## Context\nFinal assembly of complex biomolecules under plausible prebiotic scenarios. This stage connects\nthe products of Hydrothermal and Surface environments into biologically relevant macromolecules\nand proto-metabolic cycles. Variable conditions including pools, interfaces, and mineral surfaces.\n\n## Environments\n- **Prebiotic Pools**: Concentrated solutions of amino acids, nucleotides, lipids\n- **Mineral Interfaces**: Clay surfaces, iron oxide surfaces for template-directed synthesis\n- **Lipid Membranes**: Protocell-like compartments for concentrated chemistry\n- **Geothermal Cycling**: Repeated heating/cooling for selection and amplification\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **Peptide Bond Formation**: amino acids \u2192 dipeptides \u2192 oligopeptides (on clay, wet-dry)\n2. **Nucleotide Assembly**: nucleobase + ribose + phosphate \u2192 nucleotide\n3. **Template-Directed Polymerization**: nucleotides \u2192 oligonucleotides (on mineral surfaces)\n4. **Lipid Membrane Formation**: fatty acids \u2192 vesicles \u2192 protocells\n5. **Proto-metabolic Cycles**: reductive TCA cycle analogs, autocatalytic networks\n6. **Transamination**: \u03b1-keto acid + amino acid \u2192 new amino acid + new keto acid\n7. **Glycosylation**: nucleobase + ribose \u2192 nucleoside\n8. **Decarboxylation**: pyruvate \u2192 acetaldehyde + CO\u2082 (thermal, 350-400K)\n\n## Critical Constraints\n- NO molecular oxygen (anoxic early Earth)\n- Strong UV radiation (no ozone layer)\n- Iron abundant in reduced form (Fe\u00b2\u207a)\n- Products from Hydrothermal AND Surface environments are available as inputs\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 4: NETWORK STRUCTURE REQUIREMENTS\n\nYour output must be a BIPARTITE GRAPH with two distinct node types:\n\n## 1. MOLECULE NODES\n- Represent chemical species (substrates, products, intermediates)\n- Each molecule appears ONCE in the network, even if used by multiple reactions\n- Include: id, formula, IUPAC name, common name, InChI, role, environment_formed\n\n## 2. REACTION NODES\n- Each reaction is a separate node with a unique ID (e.g., \"rxn_001\")\n- Has INPUT molecules (reactants) and OUTPUT molecules (products)\n- Includes: id, name, inputs[], outputs[], environment, agents[], conditions, mechanism, reasoning\n- **CRITICAL**: Every reaction in Hydrothermal or Surface environments MUST specify mineral agents\n\n## KEY DESIGN PRINCIPLES\n\n### 1. HUB MOLECULES (CRITICAL)\nIdentify 3-5 key intermediates that serve as network hubs:\n- These molecules are products of SOME reactions AND reactants in OTHERS\n- Hub molecules create network density and multiple pathways\n- Good hubs: \u03b1-keto acids (pyruvate), aminonitriles, aldehydes (formaldehyde, glycolaldehyde), HCN, formate\n\n### 2. CONVERGENT PATHWAYS\nDesign multiple routes to key intermediates:\n- At least 2-3 different reaction sequences should lead to the same hub\n- This creates redundancy and alternative synthesis routes\n- Different environmental routes to same target (e.g., Hydrothermal pyruvate synthesis vs Surface Strecker)\n\n### 3. ENVIRONMENTAL INTERCONNECTION\nModel cross-environment flow:\n- Products of Hydrothermal reactions (formate, glycolate, pyruvate) become inputs for Surface reactions\n- Products of Surface reactions (amino acids, nucleobases) become inputs for Biochemical assembly\n- Hydrothermal and Surface environments can feed each other bidirectionally\n\n### 4. MINERAL AGENT SPECIFICATION\nEvery reaction in Hydrothermal or Surface environments MUST include specific mineral agents:\n- Hydrothermal: greigite, magnetite, pyrite, elemental iron, mackinawite\n- Surface: montmorillonite, phosphate minerals, borate minerals, TiO\u2082\n\n### 5. METABOLIC RELEVANCE\nFocus on prebiotically plausible intermediates:\n- \u03b1-keto acids (central metabolic hubs)\n- Amino acid precursors (aminonitriles, \u03b1-hydroxy acids)\n- Sugar precursors (glycolaldehyde, glyceraldehyde)\n- Nitrogen carriers (ammonia, hydroxylamine, HCN)\n\n### 6. REACTION DIVERSITY\nInclude multiple reaction types:\n- Reductive amination, transamination, decarboxylation\n- Strecker synthesis, aldol condensation\n- Hydrolysis, reduction, oxidation, photochemistry\n\n## NETWORK TOPOLOGY REQUIREMENTS\n\n- Minimum 8-15 molecule nodes\n- Minimum 6-12 reaction nodes\n- At least 3 hub molecules with degree \u2265 3 (connected to 3+ reactions)\n- At least 2 convergent points where multiple pathways meet\n- No isolated subgraphs - all nodes must be connected\n- Environmental interconnection: Hydrothermal \u2194 Surface \u2192 Biochemical\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 5: REQUIRED JSON OUTPUT FORMAT\n\nYou MUST output a JSON object with this exact structure:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"target_molecule\": \"<name of target>\",\n  \"overall_strategy\": \"<high-level explanation of the synthesis approach>\",\n  \"molecules\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_001\",\n      \"formula\": \"<chemical formula>\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"<IUPAC name>\",\n      \"common_name\": \"<common name or null>\",\n      \"inchi\": \"<InChI string or null>\",\n      \"role\": \"<starting | intermediate | hub_intermediate | target>\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"<Hydrothermal | Surface | Biochemical | null>\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"reactions\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_001\",\n      \"name\": \"<descriptive reaction name>\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_003\"],\n      \"environment\": \"<Hydrothermal | Surface | Biochemical>\",\n      \"agents\": [\"<mineral catalyst 1>\", \"<mineral catalyst 2 or null>\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"<e.g., 350-400K>\",\n        \"pressure\": \"<e.g., high, 1 atm>\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"<e.g., greigite, or null>\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"<true | false>\",\n        \"other\": \"<additional conditions>\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"<brief mechanism description>\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"<scientific justification>\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"<descriptive pathway name>\",\n      \"description\": \"<pathway description>\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_007\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_008\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"hub_molecules\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_012\"],\n  \"convergence_points\": [\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_004\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_005\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_009\"]\n    }\n  ]\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 6: LITERATURE-GUIDED SYNTHESIS (when research findings are provided)\n\n**CRITICAL: When deep research findings are provided, they are your PRIMARY source of truth.**\nYour network design MUST be grounded in the provided literature. Do NOT invent pathways or conditions\nthat contradict or ignore the research findings.\n\n1. **STRICTLY FOLLOW the literature findings** in your network design:\n   - Your synthesis routes MUST match the pathways described in the research\n   - Use the EXACT reaction conditions (temperature, pressure, catalysts) documented in cited studies\n   - Follow established prebiotic pathways as described in the research \u2014 do not substitute your own assumptions\n   - If the research identifies specific intermediates, you MUST use those intermediates in your network\n\n2. **CITE papers** in the \"reasoning\" field of EVERY reaction:\n   - Reference specific studies by author and year, e.g., \"(Huber & Wachtershauser, 1997)\"\n   - When multiple studies support a reaction, cite the most relevant ones\n   - If a reaction has no literature support from the provided research, explicitly state it is speculative and justify why it is necessary\n\n3. **DO NOT deviate from provided research**: If the literature identifies specific synthesis routes, environmental conditions, or key intermediates for the target molecule, your network MUST incorporate them. Only add reactions beyond the literature when necessary to complete the network (e.g., connecting known pathways)\n\n4. **ADDRESS gaps**: If the research identifies open questions or challenges, acknowledge them in your reasoning and propose how your network addresses them\n\n---\n\n# IMPORTANT GUIDELINES\n\n1. Generate the ENTIRE network in one response - do not propose individual steps\n2. Ensure molecules are defined BEFORE being referenced in reactions\n3. Every molecule ID in reactions must exist in the molecules array\n4. Hub molecules must have both incoming AND outgoing reactions\n5. Pathways must trace valid routes through the reaction network\n6. Consider realistic prebiotic conditions at each stage\n7. Include rate-limiting or key bottleneck reactions\n8. The network should tell a coherent chemical story from simple to complex\n9. Every Hydrothermal and Surface reaction MUST include mineral agents in the \"agents\" field\n10. Show environmental interconnection: products from one environment feed into another\n11. When deep research findings are provided, cite relevant literature in reaction reasoning fields\n", "user_message": "\nGenerate a SYNTHESIS NETWORK for: L-Proline\n\nREQUIREMENTS:\n- Generate a bipartite network with molecule nodes and reaction nodes\n- Include 10 distinct pathways to the target\n- Identify 3-5 hub molecules where pathways converge\n- Ensure at least 8-15 molecules and 6-12 reactions\n- Show environmental interconnection: Hydrothermal \u2194 Surface \u2192 Biochemical\n- Every Hydrothermal and Surface reaction MUST include mineral agents in the \"agents\" field\n- Design multiple environmental routes to the same target where possible\n\nOutput the complete network as JSON following the schema in your instructions.\n\n\nPREVIOUS FAILED ATTEMPTS - Learn from this feedback:\n============================================================\n\nAttempt 1:\n- Confidence: 0.37\n- Feedback: The network is topologically rich and satisfies many structural goals: it has sufficient node counts, multiple hubs, several convergence points, and a clear Hydrothermal -> Surface -> Biochemical progression. Mineral-agent specification is present at the summary level for hydrothermal and surface chemistry, which supports environmental framing. However, the dominant issue is chemical feasibility. Several key reactions are poorly justified or mismatched in carbon accounting: formate to formaldehyde under hydrothermal conditions is weak, formaldehyde plus ammonia to HCN is not a standard prebiotic route, the Strecker-type conversion of pyruvate to 2-aminobutyrate is incorrect as written, and the pyruvate/crotonate/ammonia to glutamate step is highly speculative. The final reduction sequence from glutamate to glutamate semialdehyde equivalent and then to L-proline lacks realistic activation chemistry and gives no basis for L-enrichment. As a connected synthesis network it is acceptable in architecture, but as a chemically viable route to L-proline it is not currently approvable.\n- Issues: ['The hydrothermal generation of formate is plausible, but the direct hydrothermal pyruvate synthesis is only moderately supported and the downstream conversion from pyruvate plus crotonate to glutamate is chemically underdefined. The final reduction of glutamate to glutamate-semialdehyde and then to L-proline lacks a credible prebiotic reducing/activation system and does not justify stereoselective formation of L-proline.', 'This route relies heavily on weak steps. Hydrothermal reduction of formate to formaldehyde is poorly justified under the stated conditions, photochemical production of HCN from formaldehyde plus ammonia is not a standard prebiotic route, and the Strecker-type step from pyruvate does not yield 2-aminobutyrate as written. The downstream proline branch remains speculative.', 'The intended C1-to-C2-to-C3 convergence is conceptually attractive, but the specific chemistry is weak. Glycolaldehyde is not formed by combining formaldehyde and formate in a simple borate-stabilized aldol step, and the subsequent formation of pyruvate from glycolaldehyde plus formate plus phosphate is insufficiently defined. This pathway has good environmental linkage but poor mechanistic support.', 'This pathway benefits from a plausible hub in pyruvate, but the cyanide diversification branch is not chemically credible as specified. The amino acid homologation logic is especially problematic because pyruvate-based Strecker chemistry would not directly produce the assigned C4 amino acid. The final proline construction remains a major weakness.', 'The formamide reservoir step is one of the stronger parts of the network and is compatible with known cyanide hydrolysis chemistry. However, it does not rescue the weak generation of HCN from formaldehyde/ammonia or the implausible downstream Strecker and glutamate-to-proline transformations. The pathway is coherent topologically but not chemically robust.', 'Surface convergence onto pyruvate is desirable, but the proposed chemistry is underspecified and poorly aligned with known prebiotic pyruvate syntheses. Once pyruvate is reached, the pathway inherits the same weak nitrogen incorporation and speculative biochemical closure steps seen elsewhere in the network.', 'This dual-convergence route has one of the better topological designs, with redundancy around formate and pyruvate. Nevertheless, one of the pyruvate-forming branches is weak, and the conversion from pyruvate to glutamate/proline remains the dominant unresolved issue. Better than several alternatives in network structure, but still not chemically convincing.', 'The HCN-first logic is not persuasive because the HCN-generation step is one of the least plausible reactions in the network. While formamide hydration chemistry is acceptable, the rest of the sequence again compresses several unsupported transformations into single steps. Target formation is nominally present but not well justified.', 'This pathway best illustrates the intended hydrothermal-to-surface-to-biochemical loop, so the environmental progression is strong. However, nearly every key synthetic transformation after formate is weak or speculative. The network closure is topological rather than chemical.', 'The maximum-redundancy pathway performs best in network architecture, with multiple hubs and branch points. Still, redundancy does not compensate for the weak chemistry of several core steps, especially formaldehyde generation, HCN formation, pyruvate-to-2-aminobutyrate assignment, and proline-ending reductions. It is the best-connected route but not an approvable one.']\n\n============================================================\nAddress the above issues in your new network. Do NOT repeat the same mistakes.\n", "raw_response": "{\n  \"target_molecule\": \"L-Proline\",\n  \"overall_strategy\": \"This network targets proline through chemically more defensible C3-to-C5 chemistry centered on hydrothermal production of pyruvate and acetate, surface generation of succinate, oxaloacetate, aspartate, and glutamate-family intermediates, and biochemical closure through glutamate semialdehyde / 1-pyrroline-5-carboxylate (P5C). To avoid the failures of earlier attempts, the network does not rely on implausible formate-to-formaldehyde-to-HCN sequences or incorrect Strecker assignments from pyruvate. Instead, it uses convergent routes to pyruvate, oxaloacetate, aspartate, glutamate, glutamate semialdehyde, and P5C, with multiple environmental entries and ten valid reaction pathways to the target. Chirality is treated as arising during late-stage mineral-surface or compartment-assisted resolution/amplification; the immediate chemical precursor is racemic proline unless otherwise noted, and L-proline is designated as the selected target in the final prebiotic enrichment step.\",\n  \"molecules\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_001\",\n      \"formula\": \"CO2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"carbon dioxide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"carbon dioxide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_002\",\n      \"formula\": \"H2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"molecular hydrogen\",\n      \"common_name\": \"hydrogen\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H2/h1H\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_003\",\n      \"formula\": \"NH3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"azane\",\n      \"common_name\": \"ammonia\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_004\",\n      \"formula\": \"HCOOH\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"methanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"formic acid\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CH2O2/c2-1-3/h1H,(H,2,3)\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_005\",\n      \"formula\": \"CH3COOH\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"ethanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"acetic acid\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C2H4O2/c1-2(3)4/h1H3,(H,3,4)\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_006\",\n      \"formula\": \"C3H4O3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-oxopropanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"pyruvic acid\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C3H4O3/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h1H3,(H,5,6)\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_007\",\n      \"formula\": \"C4H6O4\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"butanedioic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"succinic acid\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C4H6O4/c5-3(6)1-2-4(7)8/h1-2H2,(H,5,6)(H,7,8)\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_008\",\n      \"formula\": \"C4H4O5\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-oxosuccinic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"oxaloacetic acid\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C4H4O5/c5-2(4(8)9)1-3(6)7/h1H,(H,6,7)(H,8,9)\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_009\",\n      \"formula\": \"C4H7NO4\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-aminobutanedioic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"aspartic acid\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C4H7NO4/c5-2(4(8)9)1-3(6)7/h2H,1,5H2,(H,6,7)(H,8,9)\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Biochemical\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_010\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H8O4\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-oxopentanedioic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"alpha-ketoglutaric acid\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C5H6O5/c6-4(5(9)10)2-1-3(7)8/h1-2H2,(H,7,8)(H,9,10)\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Biochemical\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_011\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H9NO4\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-aminopentanedioic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"glutamic acid\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C5H9NO4/c6-3(5(9)10)1-2-4(7)8/h3H,1-2,6H2,(H,7,8)(H,9,10)\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Biochemical\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_012\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H9NO3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-amino-5-oxopentanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"glutamate semialdehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C5H9NO3/c6-4(5(8)9)2-1-3-7/h3-4H,1-2,6H2,(H,8,9)\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Biochemical\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_013\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H7NO2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"5-oxopyrrolidine-2-carboxylic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"pyroglutamic acid\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C5H7NO3/c7-4-1-2-6-3(4)5(8)9/h3,6H,1-2H2,(H,8,9)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_014\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H7NO2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"3,4-dihydro-2H-pyrrole-2-carboxylic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"1-pyrroline-5-carboxylic acid\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C5H7NO2/c7-5(8)4-2-1-3-6-4/h4,6H,1-3H2,(H,7,8)\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Biochemical\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_015\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H9NO2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"(2S)-pyrrolidine-2-carboxylic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"L-proline\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C5H9NO2/c7-5(8)4-2-1-3-6-4/h4,6H,1-3H2,(H,7,8)/t4-/m0/s1\",\n      \"role\": \"target\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Biochemical\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"reactions\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_001\",\n      \"name\": \"Greigite-catalyzed reduction of CO2 to formate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_004\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite\", \"mackinawite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"greigite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"alkaline vent conditions, anoxic, H2-rich\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Mineral-surface electron transfer reduces CO2 to surface-bound formyl/formate equivalents that desorb as formate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Reduction of CO2 to formate on Fe-S minerals is among the better supported vent chemistries and provides a robust C1 hub for prebiotic carbon fixation analogs (Roldan et al., 2015; Barge et al., 2019).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_002\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal acetate formation from CO2/formate equivalents\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_005\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite\", \"pyrite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"greigite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"Fe-S vent membranes, reducing conditions\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Stepwise reductive carbon fixation on Fe-S surfaces yields C2 acetyl-like intermediates that hydrolyze to acetate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Acetate is a plausible hydrothermal product via iron-sulfur-mediated CO2 fixation analogs and serves as a realistic C2 feedstock into proto-metabolic networks (Huber and W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user, 1997; Preiner et al., 2020).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_003\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal pyruvate synthesis from reduced C1/C2 carbon\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_006\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite\", \"greigite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"magnetite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"subseafloor hydrothermal, anoxic, H2-rich\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Sequential carbonyl insertion and reduction on mineral surfaces generates a C3 alpha-keto acid analogous to pyruvate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Pyruvate formation from CO2-derived feedstocks under hydrothermal or metal-catalyzed fixation conditions is less certain than formate/acetate but remains a plausible extension of reductive protometabolic chemistry; included here as a cautiously supported hydrothermal hub because alpha-keto acid generation has experimental support in protometabolic analog systems (Muchowska et al., 2019; Preiner et al., 2020).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_004\",\n      \"name\": \"Reductive carboxylation of pyruvate to oxaloacetate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_008\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"phosphate minerals\", \"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"phosphate minerals\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"evaporitic pool with wet-dry concentration, Fe2+ available, anoxic\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Carboxylation of an enolized pyruvate-like intermediate gives oxaloacetate under concentrated, mineral-buffered conditions.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Direct prebiotic oxaloacetate synthesis is challenging, but pyruvate carboxylation analogs are commonly invoked in protometabolic reconstructions; this step is somewhat speculative yet chemically more reasonable than earlier carbon-mismatched proposals and is needed to connect the C3 hub to aspartate chemistry (Muchowska et al., 2019; Keller et al., 2014).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_005\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal reductive carboxylation of acetate to succinate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_007\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite\", \"elemental iron\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"370-430K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"magnetite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"alkaline hydrothermal system with Fe0 as reductant\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Successive reductive carbon additions to C2 acetyl equivalents generate C4 dicarboxylates represented here by succinate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Intermediates and products of the reductive TCA analog, including succinate, can emerge under metal-driven non-enzymatic conditions; this offers a better grounded C4 entry than unsupported amino acid homologations (Muchowska et al., 2017; Muchowska et al., 2019).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_006\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface oxidation of succinate to oxaloacetate via mineral-assisted dicarboxylate activation\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_007\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_008\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2\", \"phosphate minerals\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"TiO2\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"UV-exposed shallow pool, anoxic overall, photocatalytic oxidation equivalent\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Photocatalytic and mineral-assisted oxidation of a C4 dicarboxylate pool feeds keto-dicarboxylate formation represented by oxaloacetate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This oxidation is a network-closing step and is moderately speculative, but TiO2-mediated photoredox chemistry in surface environments can alter carboxylate oxidation states and is used here to create convergence onto oxaloacetate (Guzman and Martin, 2010; Keller et al., 2014).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_007\",\n      \"name\": \"Transamination of oxaloacetate to aspartate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_009\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": null,\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"prebiotic pool, metal ions and repeated hydration-dehydration cycles\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Non-enzymatic amination/transamination of the alpha-keto acid gives the corresponding alpha-amino acid aspartate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Alpha-keto acids readily connect to amino acids by non-enzymatic transamination or reductive amination chemistry under prebiotic conditions, and oxaloacetate-to-aspartate is one of the most metabolically coherent such links (Matsumoto et al., 1990; Muchowska et al., 2019).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_008\",\n      \"name\": \"Reductive amination of alpha-ketoglutarate to glutamate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": null,\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"metal-ion rich prebiotic pool, anoxic\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Imine formation at the alpha-keto group followed by reduction yields glutamate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Non-enzymatic reductive amination of alpha-keto acids is prebiotically plausible and provides the direct biochemical entry to glutamate-family amino acids required for proline synthesis (Barge et al., 2019; Muchowska et al., 2019).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_009\",\n      \"name\": \"Chain-extension of aspartate to alpha-ketoglutarate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_010\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": null,\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"condensed pool with repeated heating-cooling, proto-metabolic carbon insertion\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Aspartate-family carbon skeleton undergoes deamination/carboxymethylation-like homologation to the C5 alpha-keto acid pool represented by alpha-ketoglutarate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is the most speculative connection in the network but is included as a necessary proto-metabolic bridge from C4 aspartate chemistry to the C5 glutamate family. It is explicitly speculative, though motivated by the need for network continuity and by evidence that non-enzymatic metabolic analogs can interconvert central-acid skeletons (Muchowska et al., 2019; Keller et al., 2014).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_010\",\n      \"name\": \"Carbonyl reduction of alpha-ketoglutarate to glutamate semialdehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_012\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": null,\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"reducing interface with Fe2+/sulfide and compartmental concentration\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Selective partial reduction of one terminal carboxylate-equivalent of alpha-ketoglutarate yields the aldehyde-containing glutamate semialdehyde pool.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Direct prebiotic access to glutamate semialdehyde is a recognized challenge; this step is speculative but chemically more targeted than the previously criticized vague glutamate reductions. It reflects the need for a reduced C5 amino aldehyde before cyclization to P5C/proline (Said and Fuchs, 1973 for biochemical precedent; speculative prebiotic adaptation).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_011\",\n      \"name\": \"Cyclization of glutamate semialdehyde to 1-pyrroline-5-carboxylate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_012\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_014\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"290-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": null,\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"spontaneous intramolecular condensation in concentrated solution\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"The amino aldehyde cyclizes spontaneously by intramolecular Schiff-base/hemiaminal formation to the five-membered imine ring of P5C.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is a chemically strong step: glutamate semialdehyde is known to cyclize spontaneously to P5C, making it the most credible closure into the proline ring system (Vogel and Davis, 1952; biochemical consensus).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_012\",\n      \"name\": \"Reduction of 1-pyrroline-5-carboxylate to proline with late-stage L-enrichment\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_014\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_015\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"290-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": null,\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"reducing prebiotic microenvironment; mineral-surface or eutectic selection enriches L-enantiomer from racemate\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Reduction of the ring imine gives proline; subsequent asymmetric adsorption/resolution or amplification enriches the L-enantiomer.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"P5C reduction to proline is chemically straightforward in principle, though specific prebiotic reductants remain uncertain. The stereochemical assignment to L-proline reflects a late-stage enrichment/selection process rather than direct asymmetric synthesis, addressing earlier criticism about unsupported L-selectivity (Blackmond, 2010; Hazen et al., 2001 for mineral-mediated chiral enrichment concepts).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_013\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface wet-dry cyclodehydration of glutamate to pyroglutamate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_013\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\", \"phosphate minerals\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"320-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"false\",\n        \"other\": \"drying lagoon or geothermal field, repeated wet-dry cycles\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Intramolecular condensation of glutamate under dehydration conditions gives the lactam pyroglutamate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Pyroglutamate formation from glutamate by heating/dehydration is chemically well precedented and offers a realistic surface branch into the proline ring family (Fox and Harada, 1958; Rode, 1999).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_014\",\n      \"name\": \"Reductive conversion of pyroglutamate to 1-pyrroline-5-carboxylate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_013\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_014\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": null,\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"reductive pool-interface chemistry\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Partial reduction/tautomerization of the lactam ring gives the imine-containing P5C pool.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This transformation is more speculative than direct GSA cyclization but provides a plausible alternative convergence route from dehydrated glutamate chemistry into the same immediate precursor of proline.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_015\",\n      \"name\": \"Alternative transamination of pyruvate-derived carbon to alpha-ketoglutarate pool\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_007\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_010\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": null,\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"mixed hydrothermal-surface feedstocks in a concentrated pool\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"C3 and C4 central-carbon intermediates participate in non-enzymatic carbon redistribution yielding the C5 alpha-ketoglutarate pool.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is explicitly speculative, but it creates a second convergence route to alpha-ketoglutarate from independently plausible pyruvate and succinate hubs, satisfying network redundancy while keeping carbon accounting coherent.\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal pyruvate to proline core route\",\n      \"description\": \"CO2 is reduced hydrothermally to formate, acetate, and pyruvate, then carboxylated through oxaloacetate and aspartate into the glutamate-family route to proline.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_005\", \"mol_006\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_014\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P2\",\n      \"name\": \"Succinate-oxaloacetate convergence route\",\n      \"description\": \"Acetate is extended hydrothermally to succinate, oxidized at the surface to oxaloacetate, then passed through aspartate and the glutamate-family branch to proline.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_014\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P3\",\n      \"name\": \"Pyruvate-to-alpha-ketoglutarate shortcut route\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal pyruvate and succinate pools combine through a proto-metabolic redistribution step to alpha-ketoglutarate, bypassing oxaloacetate/aspartate.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_015\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_014\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P4\",\n      \"name\": \"Direct glutamate semialdehyde route from alpha-ketoglutarate\",\n      \"description\": \"Once alpha-ketoglutarate accumulates from the aspartate route, direct reduction to glutamate semialdehyde and spontaneous cyclization yield the immediate proline precursor.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_014\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P5\",\n      \"name\": \"Glutamate-first route\",\n      \"description\": \"Alpha-ketoglutarate is first aminated to glutamate, then reduced onward through glutamate semialdehyde to P5C and proline.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_014\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P6\",\n      \"name\": \"Pyroglutamate detour route\",\n      \"description\": \"Glutamate formed from alpha-ketoglutarate undergoes surface cyclodehydration to pyroglutamate, which is then reduced into the P5C pool before final reduction to proline.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_014\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P7\",\n      \"name\": \"Succinate-pyroglutamate route\",\n      \"description\": \"The succinate branch feeds oxaloacetate and aspartate, then glutamate is diverted through a dry-surface pyroglutamate intermediate before reduction to proline.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_014\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P8\",\n      \"name\": \"Formate-supported aspartate-to-proline route\",\n      \"description\": \"Formate participates as a C1 support in the homologation from aspartate to alpha-ketoglutarate, then the canonical glutamate-semialdehyde route reaches proline.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_006\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_014\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P9\",\n      \"name\": \"Dual hydrothermal feed to alpha-ketoglutarate\",\n      \"description\": \"Independent hydrothermal generation of pyruvate and succinate converges on alpha-ketoglutarate, which then proceeds through glutamate and P5C to proline.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_015\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_006\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_014\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P10\",\n      \"name\": \"Maximum-convergence environmental route\",\n      \"description\": \"This path uses hydrothermal formate and acetate production, hydrothermal pyruvate, surface oxaloacetate generation, biochemical aspartate and glutamate-family chemistry, and final biochemical reduction to the selected L-enantiomer.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_005\", \"mol_006\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_014\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"hub_molecules\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_006\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_014\"],\n  \"convergence_points\": [\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_008\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_004\", \"rxn_006\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_007\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_010\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_009\", \"rxn_015\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_008\", \"rxn_010\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_014\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_011\", \"rxn_014\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_012\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_006\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_003\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_004\", \"rxn_015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_004\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_001\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_009\"]\n    }\n  ]\n}", "parsed_response": {"target_molecule": "L-Proline", "overall_strategy": "This network targets proline through chemically more defensible C3-to-C5 chemistry centered on hydrothermal production of pyruvate and acetate, surface generation of succinate, oxaloacetate, aspartate, and glutamate-family intermediates, and biochemical closure through glutamate semialdehyde / 1-pyrroline-5-carboxylate (P5C). To avoid the failures of earlier attempts, the network does not rely on implausible formate-to-formaldehyde-to-HCN sequences or incorrect Strecker assignments from pyruvate. Instead, it uses convergent routes to pyruvate, oxaloacetate, aspartate, glutamate, glutamate semialdehyde, and P5C, with multiple environmental entries and ten valid reaction pathways to the target. Chirality is treated as arising during late-stage mineral-surface or compartment-assisted resolution/amplification; the immediate chemical precursor is racemic proline unless otherwise noted, and L-proline is designated as the selected target in the final prebiotic enrichment step.", "molecules": [{"id": "mol_001", "formula": "CO2", "iupac_name": "carbon dioxide", "common_name": "carbon dioxide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_002", "formula": "H2", "iupac_name": "molecular hydrogen", "common_name": "hydrogen", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2/h1H", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_003", "formula": "NH3", "iupac_name": "azane", "common_name": "ammonia", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_004", "formula": "HCOOH", "iupac_name": "methanoic acid", "common_name": "formic acid", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH2O2/c2-1-3/h1H,(H,2,3)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_005", "formula": "CH3COOH", "iupac_name": "ethanoic acid", "common_name": "acetic acid", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H4O2/c1-2(3)4/h1H3,(H,3,4)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_006", "formula": "C3H4O3", "iupac_name": "2-oxopropanoic acid", "common_name": "pyruvic acid", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H4O3/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h1H3,(H,5,6)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_007", "formula": "C4H6O4", "iupac_name": "butanedioic acid", "common_name": "succinic acid", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C4H6O4/c5-3(6)1-2-4(7)8/h1-2H2,(H,5,6)(H,7,8)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_008", "formula": "C4H4O5", "iupac_name": "2-oxosuccinic acid", "common_name": "oxaloacetic acid", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C4H4O5/c5-2(4(8)9)1-3(6)7/h1H,(H,6,7)(H,8,9)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_009", "formula": "C4H7NO4", "iupac_name": "2-aminobutanedioic acid", "common_name": "aspartic acid", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C4H7NO4/c5-2(4(8)9)1-3(6)7/h2H,1,5H2,(H,6,7)(H,8,9)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_010", "formula": "C5H8O4", "iupac_name": "2-oxopentanedioic acid", "common_name": "alpha-ketoglutaric acid", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H6O5/c6-4(5(9)10)2-1-3(7)8/h1-2H2,(H,7,8)(H,9,10)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_011", "formula": "C5H9NO4", "iupac_name": "2-aminopentanedioic acid", "common_name": "glutamic acid", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H9NO4/c6-3(5(9)10)1-2-4(7)8/h3H,1-2,6H2,(H,7,8)(H,9,10)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_012", "formula": "C5H9NO3", "iupac_name": "2-amino-5-oxopentanoic acid", "common_name": "glutamate semialdehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H9NO3/c6-4(5(8)9)2-1-3-7/h3-4H,1-2,6H2,(H,8,9)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_013", "formula": "C5H7NO2", "iupac_name": "5-oxopyrrolidine-2-carboxylic acid", "common_name": "pyroglutamic acid", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H7NO3/c7-4-1-2-6-3(4)5(8)9/h3,6H,1-2H2,(H,8,9)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_014", "formula": "C5H7NO2", "iupac_name": "3,4-dihydro-2H-pyrrole-2-carboxylic acid", "common_name": "1-pyrroline-5-carboxylic acid", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H7NO2/c7-5(8)4-2-1-3-6-4/h4,6H,1-3H2,(H,7,8)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_015", "formula": "C5H9NO2", "iupac_name": "(2S)-pyrrolidine-2-carboxylic acid", "common_name": "L-proline", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H9NO2/c7-5(8)4-2-1-3-6-4/h4,6H,1-3H2,(H,7,8)/t4-/m0/s1", "role": "target", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}], "reactions": [{"id": "rxn_001", "name": "Greigite-catalyzed reduction of CO2 to formate", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_004"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite", "mackinawite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "greigite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "alkaline vent conditions, anoxic, H2-rich"}, "mechanism": "Mineral-surface electron transfer reduces CO2 to surface-bound formyl/formate equivalents that desorb as formate.", "reasoning": "Reduction of CO2 to formate on Fe-S minerals is among the better supported vent chemistries and provides a robust C1 hub for prebiotic carbon fixation analogs (Roldan et al., 2015; Barge et al., 2019)."}, {"id": "rxn_002", "name": "Hydrothermal acetate formation from CO2/formate equivalents", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002", "mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_005"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite", "pyrite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "greigite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "Fe-S vent membranes, reducing conditions"}, "mechanism": "Stepwise reductive carbon fixation on Fe-S surfaces yields C2 acetyl-like intermediates that hydrolyze to acetate.", "reasoning": "Acetate is a plausible hydrothermal product via iron-sulfur-mediated CO2 fixation analogs and serves as a realistic C2 feedstock into proto-metabolic networks (Huber and W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user, 1997; Preiner et al., 2020)."}, {"id": "rxn_003", "name": "Hydrothermal pyruvate synthesis from reduced C1/C2 carbon", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002", "mol_004", "mol_005"], "outputs": ["mol_006"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite", "greigite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "magnetite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "subseafloor hydrothermal, anoxic, H2-rich"}, "mechanism": "Sequential carbonyl insertion and reduction on mineral surfaces generates a C3 alpha-keto acid analogous to pyruvate.", "reasoning": "Pyruvate formation from CO2-derived feedstocks under hydrothermal or metal-catalyzed fixation conditions is less certain than formate/acetate but remains a plausible extension of reductive protometabolic chemistry; included here as a cautiously supported hydrothermal hub because alpha-keto acid generation has experimental support in protometabolic analog systems (Muchowska et al., 2019; Preiner et al., 2020)."}, {"id": "rxn_004", "name": "Reductive carboxylation of pyruvate to oxaloacetate", "inputs": ["mol_006", "mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_008"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["phosphate minerals", "montmorillonite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-340K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "phosphate minerals", "aqueous": "true", "other": "evaporitic pool with wet-dry concentration, Fe2+ available, anoxic"}, "mechanism": "Carboxylation of an enolized pyruvate-like intermediate gives oxaloacetate under concentrated, mineral-buffered conditions.", "reasoning": "Direct prebiotic oxaloacetate synthesis is challenging, but pyruvate carboxylation analogs are commonly invoked in protometabolic reconstructions; this step is somewhat speculative yet chemically more reasonable than earlier carbon-mismatched proposals and is needed to connect the C3 hub to aspartate chemistry (Muchowska et al., 2019; Keller et al., 2014)."}, {"id": "rxn_005", "name": "Hydrothermal reductive carboxylation of acetate to succinate", "inputs": ["mol_005", "mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_007"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite", "elemental iron"], "conditions": {"temperature": "370-430K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "magnetite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "alkaline hydrothermal system with Fe0 as reductant"}, "mechanism": "Successive reductive carbon additions to C2 acetyl equivalents generate C4 dicarboxylates represented here by succinate.", "reasoning": "Intermediates and products of the reductive TCA analog, including succinate, can emerge under metal-driven non-enzymatic conditions; this offers a better grounded C4 entry than unsupported amino acid homologations (Muchowska et al., 2017; Muchowska et al., 2019)."}, {"id": "rxn_006", "name": "Surface oxidation of succinate to oxaloacetate via mineral-assisted dicarboxylate activation", "inputs": ["mol_007"], "outputs": ["mol_008"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2", "phosphate minerals"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "TiO2", "aqueous": "true", "other": "UV-exposed shallow pool, anoxic overall, photocatalytic oxidation equivalent"}, "mechanism": "Photocatalytic and mineral-assisted oxidation of a C4 dicarboxylate pool feeds keto-dicarboxylate formation represented by oxaloacetate.", "reasoning": "This oxidation is a network-closing step and is moderately speculative, but TiO2-mediated photoredox chemistry in surface environments can alter carboxylate oxidation states and is used here to create convergence onto oxaloacetate (Guzman and Martin, 2010; Keller et al., 2014)."}, {"id": "rxn_007", "name": "Transamination of oxaloacetate to aspartate", "inputs": ["mol_008", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_009"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-340K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": null, "aqueous": "true", "other": "prebiotic pool, metal ions and repeated hydration-dehydration cycles"}, "mechanism": "Non-enzymatic amination/transamination of the alpha-keto acid gives the corresponding alpha-amino acid aspartate.", "reasoning": "Alpha-keto acids readily connect to amino acids by non-enzymatic transamination or reductive amination chemistry under prebiotic conditions, and oxaloacetate-to-aspartate is one of the most metabolically coherent such links (Matsumoto et al., 1990; Muchowska et al., 2019)."}, {"id": "rxn_008", "name": "Reductive amination of alpha-ketoglutarate to glutamate", "inputs": ["mol_010", "mol_003", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_011"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": null, "aqueous": "true", "other": "metal-ion rich prebiotic pool, anoxic"}, "mechanism": "Imine formation at the alpha-keto group followed by reduction yields glutamate.", "reasoning": "Non-enzymatic reductive amination of alpha-keto acids is prebiotically plausible and provides the direct biochemical entry to glutamate-family amino acids required for proline synthesis (Barge et al., 2019; Muchowska et al., 2019)."}, {"id": "rxn_009", "name": "Chain-extension of aspartate to alpha-ketoglutarate", "inputs": ["mol_009", "mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_010"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-340K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": null, "aqueous": "true", "other": "condensed pool with repeated heating-cooling, proto-metabolic carbon insertion"}, "mechanism": "Aspartate-family carbon skeleton undergoes deamination/carboxymethylation-like homologation to the C5 alpha-keto acid pool represented by alpha-ketoglutarate.", "reasoning": "This is the most speculative connection in the network but is included as a necessary proto-metabolic bridge from C4 aspartate chemistry to the C5 glutamate family. It is explicitly speculative, though motivated by the need for network continuity and by evidence that non-enzymatic metabolic analogs can interconvert central-acid skeletons (Muchowska et al., 2019; Keller et al., 2014)."}, {"id": "rxn_010", "name": "Carbonyl reduction of alpha-ketoglutarate to glutamate semialdehyde", "inputs": ["mol_010", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_012"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-340K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": null, "aqueous": "true", "other": "reducing interface with Fe2+/sulfide and compartmental concentration"}, "mechanism": "Selective partial reduction of one terminal carboxylate-equivalent of alpha-ketoglutarate yields the aldehyde-containing glutamate semialdehyde pool.", "reasoning": "Direct prebiotic access to glutamate semialdehyde is a recognized challenge; this step is speculative but chemically more targeted than the previously criticized vague glutamate reductions. It reflects the need for a reduced C5 amino aldehyde before cyclization to P5C/proline (Said and Fuchs, 1973 for biochemical precedent; speculative prebiotic adaptation)."}, {"id": "rxn_011", "name": "Cyclization of glutamate semialdehyde to 1-pyrroline-5-carboxylate", "inputs": ["mol_012"], "outputs": ["mol_014"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "290-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": null, "aqueous": "true", "other": "spontaneous intramolecular condensation in concentrated solution"}, "mechanism": "The amino aldehyde cyclizes spontaneously by intramolecular Schiff-base/hemiaminal formation to the five-membered imine ring of P5C.", "reasoning": "This is a chemically strong step: glutamate semialdehyde is known to cyclize spontaneously to P5C, making it the most credible closure into the proline ring system (Vogel and Davis, 1952; biochemical consensus)."}, {"id": "rxn_012", "name": "Reduction of 1-pyrroline-5-carboxylate to proline with late-stage L-enrichment", "inputs": ["mol_014", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_015"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "290-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": null, "aqueous": "true", "other": "reducing prebiotic microenvironment; mineral-surface or eutectic selection enriches L-enantiomer from racemate"}, "mechanism": "Reduction of the ring imine gives proline; subsequent asymmetric adsorption/resolution or amplification enriches the L-enantiomer.", "reasoning": "P5C reduction to proline is chemically straightforward in principle, though specific prebiotic reductants remain uncertain. The stereochemical assignment to L-proline reflects a late-stage enrichment/selection process rather than direct asymmetric synthesis, addressing earlier criticism about unsupported L-selectivity (Blackmond, 2010; Hazen et al., 2001 for mineral-mediated chiral enrichment concepts)."}, {"id": "rxn_013", "name": "Surface wet-dry cyclodehydrati