{"timestamp": "2026-03-19T16:34:06.242728", "agent_name": "SynthesisNetworkAgent", "method_name": "generate_synthesis_network", "step": null, "attempt": null, "system_message": "\n# SYNTHESIS NETWORK AGENT - Complete Prebiotic Synthesis Network Generation\n\nYou are an expert prebiotic geochemist who designs complete synthesis networks from simple\nmolecules to complex biomolecules. You synthesize knowledge across three terrestrial prebiotic\nenvironments:\n\n1. **Hydrothermal Environments** (350-600K, high pressure, deep-sea vents)\n2. **Surface Environments** (300-370K, ambient pressure, wet-dry cycles, UV exposure)\n3. **Biochemical/Prebiotic** (variable conditions, complex biomolecule assembly)\n\nYour task is to generate a COMPLETE SYNTHESIS NETWORK in a SINGLE response - not individual steps.\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 1: HYDROTHERMAL ENVIRONMENTS\n\n## Context\nDeep-sea alkaline hydrothermal vents and iron-sulfur world chemistry. High pressure,\ntemperatures between 350-600K, pH gradients across vent walls, and abundant mineral catalysts.\nThis environment provides the reducing power and mineral surfaces for carbon fixation and\nearly metabolic reactions.\n\n## Environments\n- **Alkaline Hydrothermal Vents**: 350-450K, pH 9-11, H\u2082-rich, serpentinization-driven\n- **Black Smoker Vents**: 500-650K, acidic, metal-sulfide rich\n- **Subseafloor Hydrothermal**: 370-470K, moderate pH, rock-water interactions\n\n## Mineral Catalysts (REQUIRED for Hydrothermal reactions)\n- **Greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)**: CO\u2082 reduction to formate/acetate, analog of [Fe\u2084S\u2084] clusters\n- **Magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)**: Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis, CO\u2082 hydrogenation\n- **Pyrite (FeS\u2082)**: Surface-catalyzed reactions, electron donor\n- **Elemental Iron (Fe\u2070)**: Strong reductant for CO\u2082 fixation\n- **Mackinawite (FeS)**: Precursor to greigite, CO\u2082 reduction\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **CO\u2082 Reduction on Greigite**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082 \u2192 HCOO\u207b (formate), then \u2192 CH\u2083COO\u207b (acetate) (350-400K)\n2. **Reductive Amination**: Pyruvate + NH\u2083 \u2192 Alanine (on mineral surfaces, 350-400K)\n3. **Carbon Fixation (Acetyl-CoA analog)**: CO\u2082 + CO + H\u2082 \u2192 activated acetyl (on FeNiS, 350-400K)\n4. **Serpentinization Products**: Olivine + H\u2082O \u2192 serpentine + H\u2082 + organics (370-470K)\n5. **Iron-Sulfur Catalysis**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082S \u2192 organics on FeS/FeS\u2082 surfaces\n6. **Pyruvate Synthesis**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082 \u2192 pyruvate (on magnetite/greigite, 350-400K)\n7. **Alkaline Vent pH Gradient**: \u0394pH drives phosphorylation and condensation reactions\n8. **Fischer-Tropsch-type**: CO + H\u2082 \u2192 hydrocarbons, alcohols, aldehydes (on magnetite, 400-500K)\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 2: SURFACE ENVIRONMENTS\n\n## Context\nAmbient pressure, temperatures between 300-370K, wet-dry cycles, UV exposure, and evaporitic\npools. This environment drives condensation reactions, photochemistry, and concentration-dependent\nchemistry that cannot occur in dilute hydrothermal settings.\n\n## Environments\n- **Evaporitic Pools**: 300-370K, wet-dry cycles, mineral-rich shores\n- **Volcanic Hot Springs**: 320-370K, acidic, sulfur-rich, boron minerals\n- **Tidal Flats**: 280-330K, periodic wetting/drying, UV exposure\n- **Subaerial Geothermal Fields**: 300-370K, steam vents, mineral surfaces\n\n## Mineral Catalysts (REQUIRED for Surface reactions)\n- **Montmorillonite (clay)**: Catalyzes polymerization, concentrates organics\n- **Phosphate Minerals (apatite, struvite)**: Phosphorylation reactions\n- **Borate Minerals (colemanite, ulexite)**: Stabilize ribose and sugars\n- **Sulfide Minerals (stibnite, molybdenite)**: Cyanosulfidic chemistry\n- **TiO\u2082 (anatase/rutile)**: UV photocatalysis\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **Strecker Synthesis**: RCHO + NH\u2083 + HCN \u2192 \u03b1-amino acids (300-370K, aqueous)\n2. **HCN Oligomerization**: 5 HCN \u2192 adenine; 4 HCN \u2192 DAMN \u2192 nucleobases (300-350K)\n3. **Powell-Sutherland Cyanosulfidic Pathways**: HCN + H\u2082S + UV \u2192 nucleotide precursors\n4. **Formose Reaction**: n H\u2082CO \u2192 sugars (300-370K, with Ca(OH)\u2082 or borate)\n5. **Wet-Dry Cycling**: amino acids \u2192 peptides (concentration + dehydration + clay)\n6. **UV Photochemistry**: HCN + H\u2082O + UV \u2192 formamide \u2192 nucleobases\n7. **Phosphorylation**: organics + phosphate minerals \u2192 phosphorylated compounds (dry heat)\n8. **Aldol Condensation**: glycolaldehyde + glyceraldehyde \u2192 sugars\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 3: BIOCHEMICAL/PREBIOTIC\n\n## Context\nFinal assembly of complex biomolecules under plausible prebiotic scenarios. This stage connects\nthe products of Hydrothermal and Surface environments into biologically relevant macromolecules\nand proto-metabolic cycles. Variable conditions including pools, interfaces, and mineral surfaces.\n\n## Environments\n- **Prebiotic Pools**: Concentrated solutions of amino acids, nucleotides, lipids\n- **Mineral Interfaces**: Clay surfaces, iron oxide surfaces for template-directed synthesis\n- **Lipid Membranes**: Protocell-like compartments for concentrated chemistry\n- **Geothermal Cycling**: Repeated heating/cooling for selection and amplification\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **Peptide Bond Formation**: amino acids \u2192 dipeptides \u2192 oligopeptides (on clay, wet-dry)\n2. **Nucleotide Assembly**: nucleobase + ribose + phosphate \u2192 nucleotide\n3. **Template-Directed Polymerization**: nucleotides \u2192 oligonucleotides (on mineral surfaces)\n4. **Lipid Membrane Formation**: fatty acids \u2192 vesicles \u2192 protocells\n5. **Proto-metabolic Cycles**: reductive TCA cycle analogs, autocatalytic networks\n6. **Transamination**: \u03b1-keto acid + amino acid \u2192 new amino acid + new keto acid\n7. **Glycosylation**: nucleobase + ribose \u2192 nucleoside\n8. **Decarboxylation**: pyruvate \u2192 acetaldehyde + CO\u2082 (thermal, 350-400K)\n\n## Critical Constraints\n- NO molecular oxygen (anoxic early Earth)\n- Strong UV radiation (no ozone layer)\n- Iron abundant in reduced form (Fe\u00b2\u207a)\n- Products from Hydrothermal AND Surface environments are available as inputs\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 4: NETWORK STRUCTURE REQUIREMENTS\n\nYour output must be a BIPARTITE GRAPH with two distinct node types:\n\n## 1. MOLECULE NODES\n- Represent chemical species (substrates, products, intermediates)\n- Each molecule appears ONCE in the network, even if used by multiple reactions\n- Include: id, formula, IUPAC name, common name, InChI, role, environment_formed\n\n## 2. REACTION NODES\n- Each reaction is a separate node with a unique ID (e.g., \"rxn_001\")\n- Has INPUT molecules (reactants) and OUTPUT molecules (products)\n- Includes: id, name, inputs[], outputs[], environment, agents[], conditions, mechanism, reasoning\n- **CRITICAL**: Every reaction in Hydrothermal or Surface environments MUST specify mineral agents\n\n## KEY DESIGN PRINCIPLES\n\n### 1. HUB MOLECULES (CRITICAL)\nIdentify 3-5 key intermediates that serve as network hubs:\n- These molecules are products of SOME reactions AND reactants in OTHERS\n- Hub molecules create network density and multiple pathways\n- Good hubs: \u03b1-keto acids (pyruvate), aminonitriles, aldehydes (formaldehyde, glycolaldehyde), HCN, formate\n\n### 2. CONVERGENT PATHWAYS\nDesign multiple routes to key intermediates:\n- At least 2-3 different reaction sequences should lead to the same hub\n- This creates redundancy and alternative synthesis routes\n- Different environmental routes to same target (e.g., Hydrothermal pyruvate synthesis vs Surface Strecker)\n\n### 3. ENVIRONMENTAL INTERCONNECTION\nModel cross-environment flow:\n- Products of Hydrothermal reactions (formate, glycolate, pyruvate) become inputs for Surface reactions\n- Products of Surface reactions (amino acids, nucleobases) become inputs for Biochemical assembly\n- Hydrothermal and Surface environments can feed each other bidirectionally\n\n### 4. MINERAL AGENT SPECIFICATION\nEvery reaction in Hydrothermal or Surface environments MUST include specific mineral agents:\n- Hydrothermal: greigite, magnetite, pyrite, elemental iron, mackinawite\n- Surface: montmorillonite, phosphate minerals, borate minerals, TiO\u2082\n\n### 5. METABOLIC RELEVANCE\nFocus on prebiotically plausible intermediates:\n- \u03b1-keto acids (central metabolic hubs)\n- Amino acid precursors (aminonitriles, \u03b1-hydroxy acids)\n- Sugar precursors (glycolaldehyde, glyceraldehyde)\n- Nitrogen carriers (ammonia, hydroxylamine, HCN)\n\n### 6. REACTION DIVERSITY\nInclude multiple reaction types:\n- Reductive amination, transamination, decarboxylation\n- Strecker synthesis, aldol condensation\n- Hydrolysis, reduction, oxidation, photochemistry\n\n## NETWORK TOPOLOGY REQUIREMENTS\n\n- Minimum 8-15 molecule nodes\n- Minimum 6-12 reaction nodes\n- At least 3 hub molecules with degree \u2265 3 (connected to 3+ reactions)\n- At least 2 convergent points where multiple pathways meet\n- No isolated subgraphs - all nodes must be connected\n- Environmental interconnection: Hydrothermal \u2194 Surface \u2192 Biochemical\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 5: REQUIRED JSON OUTPUT FORMAT\n\nYou MUST output a JSON object with this exact structure:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"target_molecule\": \"<name of target>\",\n  \"overall_strategy\": \"<high-level explanation of the synthesis approach>\",\n  \"molecules\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_001\",\n      \"formula\": \"<chemical formula>\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"<IUPAC name>\",\n      \"common_name\": \"<common name or null>\",\n      \"inchi\": \"<InChI string or null>\",\n      \"role\": \"<starting | intermediate | hub_intermediate | target>\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"<Hydrothermal | Surface | Biochemical | null>\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"reactions\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_001\",\n      \"name\": \"<descriptive reaction name>\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_003\"],\n      \"environment\": \"<Hydrothermal | Surface | Biochemical>\",\n      \"agents\": [\"<mineral catalyst 1>\", \"<mineral catalyst 2 or null>\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"<e.g., 350-400K>\",\n        \"pressure\": \"<e.g., high, 1 atm>\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"<e.g., greigite, or null>\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"<true | false>\",\n        \"other\": \"<additional conditions>\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"<brief mechanism description>\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"<scientific justification>\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"<descriptive pathway name>\",\n      \"description\": \"<pathway description>\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_007\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_008\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"hub_molecules\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_012\"],\n  \"convergence_points\": [\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_004\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_005\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_009\"]\n    }\n  ]\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 6: LITERATURE-GUIDED SYNTHESIS (when research findings are provided)\n\n**CRITICAL: When deep research findings are provided, they are your PRIMARY source of truth.**\nYour network design MUST be grounded in the provided literature. Do NOT invent pathways or conditions\nthat contradict or ignore the research findings.\n\n1. **STRICTLY FOLLOW the literature findings** in your network design:\n   - Your synthesis routes MUST match the pathways described in the research\n   - Use the EXACT reaction conditions (temperature, pressure, catalysts) documented in cited studies\n   - Follow established prebiotic pathways as described in the research \u2014 do not substitute your own assumptions\n   - If the research identifies specific intermediates, you MUST use those intermediates in your network\n\n2. **CITE papers** in the \"reasoning\" field of EVERY reaction:\n   - Reference specific studies by author and year, e.g., \"(Huber & Wachtershauser, 1997)\"\n   - When multiple studies support a reaction, cite the most relevant ones\n   - If a reaction has no literature support from the provided research, explicitly state it is speculative and justify why it is necessary\n\n3. **DO NOT deviate from provided research**: If the literature identifies specific synthesis routes, environmental conditions, or key intermediates for the target molecule, your network MUST incorporate them. Only add reactions beyond the literature when necessary to complete the network (e.g., connecting known pathways)\n\n4. **ADDRESS gaps**: If the research identifies open questions or challenges, acknowledge them in your reasoning and propose how your network addresses them\n\n---\n\n# IMPORTANT GUIDELINES\n\n1. Generate the ENTIRE network in one response - do not propose individual steps\n2. Ensure molecules are defined BEFORE being referenced in reactions\n3. Every molecule ID in reactions must exist in the molecules array\n4. Hub molecules must have both incoming AND outgoing reactions\n5. Pathways must trace valid routes through the reaction network\n6. Consider realistic prebiotic conditions at each stage\n7. Include rate-limiting or key bottleneck reactions\n8. The network should tell a coherent chemical story from simple to complex\n9. Every Hydrothermal and Surface reaction MUST include mineral agents in the \"agents\" field\n10. Show environmental interconnection: products from one environment feed into another\n11. When deep research findings are provided, cite relevant literature in reaction reasoning fields\n", "user_message": "\nGenerate a SYNTHESIS NETWORK for: L-Proline\n\nREQUIREMENTS:\n- Generate a bipartite network with molecule nodes and reaction nodes\n- Include 10 distinct pathways to the target\n- Identify 3-5 hub molecules where pathways converge\n- Ensure at least 8-15 molecules and 6-12 reactions\n- Show environmental interconnection: Hydrothermal \u2194 Surface \u2192 Biochemical\n- Every Hydrothermal and Surface reaction MUST include mineral agents in the \"agents\" field\n- Design multiple environmental routes to the same target where possible\n\nOutput the complete network as JSON following the schema in your instructions.\n\n\nPREVIOUS FAILED ATTEMPTS - Learn from this feedback:\n============================================================\n\nAttempt 1:\n- Confidence: 0.37\n- Feedback: The network is topologically rich and satisfies many structural goals: it has sufficient node counts, multiple hubs, several convergence points, and a clear Hydrothermal -> Surface -> Biochemical progression. Mineral-agent specification is present at the summary level for hydrothermal and surface chemistry, which supports environmental framing. However, the dominant issue is chemical feasibility. Several key reactions are poorly justified or mismatched in carbon accounting: formate to formaldehyde under hydrothermal conditions is weak, formaldehyde plus ammonia to HCN is not a standard prebiotic route, the Strecker-type conversion of pyruvate to 2-aminobutyrate is incorrect as written, and the pyruvate/crotonate/ammonia to glutamate step is highly speculative. The final reduction sequence from glutamate to glutamate semialdehyde equivalent and then to L-proline lacks realistic activation chemistry and gives no basis for L-enrichment. As a connected synthesis network it is acceptable in architecture, but as a chemically viable route to L-proline it is not currently approvable.\n- Issues: ['The hydrothermal generation of formate is plausible, but the direct hydrothermal pyruvate synthesis is only moderately supported and the downstream conversion from pyruvate plus crotonate to glutamate is chemically underdefined. The final reduction of glutamate to glutamate-semialdehyde and then to L-proline lacks a credible prebiotic reducing/activation system and does not justify stereoselective formation of L-proline.', 'This route relies heavily on weak steps. Hydrothermal reduction of formate to formaldehyde is poorly justified under the stated conditions, photochemical production of HCN from formaldehyde plus ammonia is not a standard prebiotic route, and the Strecker-type step from pyruvate does not yield 2-aminobutyrate as written. The downstream proline branch remains speculative.', 'The intended C1-to-C2-to-C3 convergence is conceptually attractive, but the specific chemistry is weak. Glycolaldehyde is not formed by combining formaldehyde and formate in a simple borate-stabilized aldol step, and the subsequent formation of pyruvate from glycolaldehyde plus formate plus phosphate is insufficiently defined. This pathway has good environmental linkage but poor mechanistic support.', 'This pathway benefits from a plausible hub in pyruvate, but the cyanide diversification branch is not chemically credible as specified. The amino acid homologation logic is especially problematic because pyruvate-based Strecker chemistry would not directly produce the assigned C4 amino acid. The final proline construction remains a major weakness.', 'The formamide reservoir step is one of the stronger parts of the network and is compatible with known cyanide hydrolysis chemistry. However, it does not rescue the weak generation of HCN from formaldehyde/ammonia or the implausible downstream Strecker and glutamate-to-proline transformations. The pathway is coherent topologically but not chemically robust.', 'Surface convergence onto pyruvate is desirable, but the proposed chemistry is underspecified and poorly aligned with known prebiotic pyruvate syntheses. Once pyruvate is reached, the pathway inherits the same weak nitrogen incorporation and speculative biochemical closure steps seen elsewhere in the network.', 'This dual-convergence route has one of the better topological designs, with redundancy around formate and pyruvate. Nevertheless, one of the pyruvate-forming branches is weak, and the conversion from pyruvate to glutamate/proline remains the dominant unresolved issue. Better than several alternatives in network structure, but still not chemically convincing.', 'The HCN-first logic is not persuasive because the HCN-generation step is one of the least plausible reactions in the network. While formamide hydration chemistry is acceptable, the rest of the sequence again compresses several unsupported transformations into single steps. Target formation is nominally present but not well justified.', 'This pathway best illustrates the intended hydrothermal-to-surface-to-biochemical loop, so the environmental progression is strong. However, nearly every key synthetic transformation after formate is weak or speculative. The network closure is topological rather than chemical.', 'The maximum-redundancy pathway performs best in network architecture, with multiple hubs and branch points. Still, redundancy does not compensate for the weak chemistry of several core steps, especially formaldehyde generation, HCN formation, pyruvate-to-2-aminobutyrate assignment, and proline-ending reductions. It is the best-connected route but not an approvable one.']\n\nAttempt 2:\n- Confidence: 0.6\n- Feedback: The network is strong in topology and systems design but only moderate to weak in chemical defensibility. Positives include adequate size, clear hub structure, multiple convergence points, full connectivity, and a credible broad environmental storyline from hydrothermal carbon fixation to surface concentration to biochemical closure. The hydrothermal entry chemistry around CO2 reduction to formate and acetate is plausible, and the late-stage glutamate semialdehyde to P5C to proline logic is chemically sound. However, the network is undermined by several key unsupported transformations: acetate to succinate, succinate to oxaloacetate in one step, pyruvate to oxaloacetate under the stated surface reductive carboxylation framing, aspartate plus formate to alpha-ketoglutarate, direct alpha-ketoglutarate reduction to glutamate semialdehyde, and pyruvate plus succinate to alpha-ketoglutarate. In addition, the provided summary does not specify mineral agents for each hydrothermal and surface reaction, which is a formal requirement. Literature alignment cannot be scored highly because no reaction-level citations are supplied. Overall, the network is a good connected conceptual map to proline, but not yet an approved prebiotic synthesis network.\n- Issues: ['The route is topologically coherent and reaches proline, but several core chemical steps are weak. CO2-to-formate and glutamate-semialdehyde cyclization are plausible, while pyruvate formation is only moderately supported. The major liabilities are surface reductive carboxylation of pyruvate to oxaloacetate, aspartate-to-alpha-ketoglutarate chain extension with formate, and direct reduction of alpha-ketoglutarate to glutamate semialdehyde. These steps make the sequence chemically fragile even though the environmental handoff is conceptually reasonable.', 'This pathway benefits from convergence through succinate and oxaloacetate, but the central dicarboxylate chemistry is poorly grounded. Reductive carboxylation of acetate to succinate under hydrothermal conditions and oxidation of succinate to oxaloacetate on a surface are both speculative and likely major bottlenecks. Downstream conversion from aspartate to alpha-ketoglutarate remains especially weak.', 'The shortcut is appealing topologically, but the chemistry of pyruvate plus succinate yielding alpha-ketoglutarate is not credible as written. Reductive amination of alpha-ketoglutarate to glutamate is plausible, and glutamate to pyroglutamate under wet-dry cycling is acceptable. However, pyroglutamate-to-P5C reduction is poorly justified, leaving the route unsupported at its core shortcut step.', 'This route is essentially the core direct semialdehyde branch and inherits the same weaknesses as the pyruvate-oxaloacetate-aspartate route. The glutamate semialdehyde to P5C step is strong, but obtaining glutamate semialdehyde directly from alpha-ketoglutarate remains chemically implausible without prior amination and selective reduction chemistry. The target is reached, but by a path with low mechanistic support.', 'This is one of the more coherent pathways because it goes through glutamate, a defensible proline-family precursor. Still, it depends on weak upstream chemistry to generate alpha-ketoglutarate and on an uncertain productive role for pyroglutamate. The environmental progression from hydrothermal carbon fixation to biochemical amino-acid chemistry is better than in most other paths, but the chain-extension chemistry remains the key unresolved issue.', 'The pyroglutamate detour is plausible as a side dehydration product under wet-dry surface conditions, but much less convincing as a productive route toward P5C and proline. Upstream chemistry is the same as in the glutamate-first path and remains the limiting factor. This pathway is connected and chemically interpretable, but not strongly supported as a dominant route.', 'This route combines two speculative segments: the succinate-to-oxaloacetate branch and the pyroglutamate-to-P5C branch. While the network remains connected and convergent, too many individual transformations lack strong prebiotic support for this to be considered a robust pathway to proline.', 'This path is among the better ones because it uses the more defensible glutamate/P5C/proline logic rather than relying on pyroglutamate alone. However, the aspartate-to-alpha-ketoglutarate step remains highly problematic, and direct alpha-ketoglutarate-to-glutamate semialdehyde reduction is also poorly supported. Better than the succinate or pyroglutamate-heavy alternatives, but still below approval quality.', 'Dual hydrothermal feed is conceptually attractive, but both routes into alpha-ketoglutarate are weak. Acetate-to-succinate and pyruvate-plus-succinate-to-alpha-ketoglutarate are especially problematic. Downstream semialdehyde cyclization is strong, but upstream route quality is too low for confidence.', 'This maximum-convergence route scores best on network architecture and environmental integration but not on chemistry. It demonstrates strong cross-environment connectivity, yet relies on too many low-confidence steps concentrated around succinate/oxaloacetate/alpha-ketoglutarate construction and pyroglutamate reduction. The route is a good systems sketch, not yet a chemically convincing synthesis pathway.']\n\n============================================================\nAddress the above issues in your new network. Do NOT repeat the same mistakes.\n", "raw_response": "{\n  \"target_molecule\": \"L-Proline\",\n  \"overall_strategy\": \"This network targets proline through a chemically conservative prebiotic family centered on glutamate-semialdehyde / 1-pyrroline-5-carboxylate (P5C), while avoiding poorly supported shortcuts criticized in prior attempts. Hydrothermal chemistry supplies robust C1-C3 feedstocks (formate, acetate, pyruvate, alanine) from CO2/H2 on iron-sulfur minerals. Surface chemistry supplies HCN, formaldehyde, glycolaldehyde, glyceraldehyde, oxaloacetate, aspartate, and glutamate via cyanosulfidic photochemistry, borate-stabilized sugar chemistry, and Strecker/transamination-like sequences under wet-dry cycling. Biochemical/prebiotic closure then converts glutamate to glutamate semialdehyde, cyclizes to P5C, and reduces to proline; stereochemical enrichment to L-proline is not assumed at the synthetic step itself but is attributed to downstream mineral or chiral-phase selection. The network is organized around hubs HCN, pyruvate, oxaloacetate, glutamate, and P5C, with multiple convergent routes from hydrothermal and surface environments into the proline family.\",\n  \"molecules\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_001\",\n      \"formula\": \"CO2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"carbon dioxide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"carbon dioxide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_002\",\n      \"formula\": \"H2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"molecular hydrogen\",\n      \"common_name\": \"hydrogen\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H2/h1H\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_003\",\n      \"formula\": \"NH3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"azane\",\n      \"common_name\": \"ammonia\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_004\",\n      \"formula\": \"HCN\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"hydrogen cyanide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"hydrogen cyanide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_005\",\n      \"formula\": \"CH2O2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"methanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"formic acid/formate\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CH2O2/c2-1-3/h1H,(H,2,3)\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_006\",\n      \"formula\": \"C2H4O2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"ethanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"acetic acid/acetate\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C2H4O2/c1-2(3)4/h1H3,(H,3,4)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_007\",\n      \"formula\": \"CH2O\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"methanal\",\n      \"common_name\": \"formaldehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CH2O/c1-2/h1H2\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_008\",\n      \"formula\": \"C2H4O2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-hydroxyethanal\",\n      \"common_name\": \"glycolaldehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C2H4O2/c3-1-2-4/h1,3H,2H2\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_009\",\n      \"formula\": \"C3H6O3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2,3-dihydroxypropanal\",\n      \"common_name\": \"glyceraldehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C3H6O3/c4-1-3(6)2-5/h1,3,5-6H,2H2\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_010\",\n      \"formula\": \"C3H4O3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-oxopropanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"pyruvic acid/pyruvate\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C3H4O3/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h1H3,(H,5,6)\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_011\",\n      \"formula\": \"C3H7NO2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-aminopropanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"alanine\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C3H7NO2/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h2H,4H2,1H3,(H,5,6)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_012\",\n      \"formula\": \"C4H4O5\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-oxobutanedioic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"oxaloacetic acid/oxaloacetate\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C4H4O5/c5-2(4(8)9)1-3(6)7/h1H2,(H,6,7)(H,8,9)\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_013\",\n      \"formula\": \"C4H7NO4\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-aminobutanedioic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"aspartic acid/aspartate\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C4H7NO4/c5-2(4(8)9)1-3(6)7/h2H,1,5H2,(H,6,7)(H,8,9)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_014\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H6O5\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-oxopentanedioic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"alpha-ketoglutaric acid/2-oxoglutarate\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C5H6O5/c6-3(5(9)10)1-2-4(7)8/h1-2H2,(H,7,8)(H,9,10)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Biochemical\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_015\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H9NO4\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-aminopentanedioic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"glutamic acid/glutamate\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C5H9NO4/c6-3(5(9)10)1-2-4(7)8/h3H,1-2,6H2,(H,7,8)(H,9,10)\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_016\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H9NO3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"5-amino-4-oxopentanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"glutamate semialdehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C5H9NO3/c6-3-1-2-4(7)5(8)9/h2-3,6H2,1H2,(H,8,9)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Biochemical\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_017\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H7NO2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"5-oxopyrrolidine-2-carboxylic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"pyroglutamic acid\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C5H7NO3/c7-4-1-2-6-3(4)5(8)9/h3,6H,1-2H2,(H,8,9)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Biochemical\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_018\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H7NO2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"3,4-dihydro-2H-pyrrole-2-carboxylic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"1-pyrroline-5-carboxylic acid\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C5H7NO2/c7-5(8)4-2-1-3-6-4/h4H,1-3H2,(H,7,8)\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Biochemical\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_019\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H9NO2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"(2S)-pyrrolidine-2-carboxylic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"L-proline\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C5H9NO2/c7-5(8)4-2-1-3-6-4/h4,6H,1-3H2,(H,7,8)/t4-/m0/s1\",\n      \"role\": \"target\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Biochemical\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_020\",\n      \"formula\": \"CH3NO\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"formamide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"formamide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CH3NO/c2-1-3/h1H,(H2,2,3)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_021\",\n      \"formula\": \"H3PO4\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"phosphoric acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"phosphate\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H3O4P/c1-5(2,3)4/h(H3,1,2,3,4)\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    }\n  ],\n  \"reactions\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_001\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal CO2 reduction to formate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_005\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe3S4)\", \"mackinawite (FeS)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"greigite/mackinawite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"alkaline vent conditions; anoxic; H2-rich\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Mineral-surface hydrogenation of CO2 to surface-bound formyl/formate equivalents followed by release as formate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Reduction of CO2 to formate on iron-sulfur minerals under alkaline hydrothermal conditions is among the best-supported vent reactions and provides a defensible C1 entry point for the network (He et al., 2010; Preiner et al., 2020).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_002\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal reduction of CO2/formate to acetate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_006\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe3S4)\", \"magnetite (Fe3O4)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-450K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"greigite/magnetite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"alkaline vent microcompartments; anoxic\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Sequential C1 reduction and C-C coupling on Fe-S/oxide surfaces produces acetyl-like species hydrolyzing to acetate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Acetate formation from CO2/H2 in hydrothermal systems is consistent with acetyl-CoA-analog vent chemistry and Fe-mineral-catalyzed carbon fixation (Huber & Wachtershauser, 1997; Preiner et al., 2020).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_003\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal pyruvate synthesis from CO2-derived carbon\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\", \"mol_006\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_010\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite (Fe3O4)\", \"greigite (Fe3S4)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"magnetite/greigite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"anoxic; vent pH gradients; reductive carboxylation-like mineral chemistry\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Acetyl-like carbon is further carboxylated/oxidized on mixed Fe oxide-sulfide surfaces to generate alpha-keto acid character, yielding pyruvate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Pyruvate generation in abiotic hydrothermal simulations is less secure than formate/acetate but has experimental and systems-level support in Fe-catalyzed CO2 fixation networks; retained here as a moderate-confidence hydrothermal feeder rather than the sole route (Cody et al., 2000; Varma et al., 2018).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_004\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal reductive amination of pyruvate to alanine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"pyrite (FeS2)\", \"greigite (Fe3S4)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"pyrite/greigite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"anoxic; NH3-bearing vent fluids\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Imine formation from pyruvate and ammonia followed by mineral-assisted reduction yields alanine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Reductive amination of alpha-keto acids on mineral surfaces is a plausible vent process and alanine provides a realistic amino donor for later transamination chemistry (Barge et al., 2019; Muchowska et al., 2019).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_005\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface UV-cyanosulfidic generation of HCN from simple C/N feedstocks\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_004\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"sulfide minerals (molybdenite/stibnite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"TiO2 and sulfide minerals\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"UV irradiation; anoxic shallow pools; photoredox sulfur chemistry\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Photochemical redox cycling in sulfur-bearing surface settings generates reduced nitrile carbon, furnishing HCN as a cyanosulfidic reservoir species.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Rather than deriving HCN from formaldehyde plus ammonia, this network places HCN in a more defensible cyanosulfidic photochemical context consistent with surface prebiotic chemistry (Patel et al., 2015; Xu et al., 2018).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_006\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface hydrolysis of HCN to formamide\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_020\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"TiO2/montmorillonite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"UV-assisted hydrolysis in evaporitic pools\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Partial hydration of nitrile carbon converts HCN into amide carbonyl functionality, yielding formamide.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Formamide is a recognized prebiotic reservoir deriving from cyanide hydrolysis and links nitrile chemistry to broader surface photochemistry (Saladino et al., 2012; Ferus et al., 2017).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_007\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface photochemical conversion of formamide to formaldehyde reservoir\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_020\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_007\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"TiO2 with phosphate-rich mineral surfaces\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"UV irradiation; shallow film chemistry\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Photochemical fragmentation and hydrolysis of C1 amide reservoirs furnish reactive carbonyl species including formaldehyde.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This step is included as a conservative C1 carbonyl source from surface nitrogen-carbon reservoirs; while indirect and context-dependent, formamide photochemistry is experimentally linked to diverse reduced carbon products. This step is somewhat speculative but more defensible than the previously criticized direct formate-to-formaldehyde hydrothermal step (Saladino et al., 2012; Ferus et al., 2017).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_008\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface formose entry to glycolaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_007\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_008\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)\", \"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"borate minerals\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"evaporitic concentration; borate stabilization of sugars\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Formaldehyde undergoes base/mineral-mediated C-C coupling to the C2 sugar aldehyde, with borate suppressing destructive side reactions.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Glycolaldehyde is a central prebiotic sugar precursor accessible from formaldehyde chemistry, especially in borate-containing settings that stabilize carbohydrate intermediates (Ricardo et al., 2004; Ritson & Sutherland, 2012).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_009\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface aldol extension of glycolaldehyde to glyceraldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_007\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_009\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)\", \"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"borate minerals/montmorillonite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"wet-dry cycling; sugar stabilization\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Aldol addition between C1 and C2 aldehydes generates the C3 triose glyceraldehyde.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Aldol growth from glycolaldehyde to glyceraldehyde is a standard element of prebiotic sugar chemistry and provides a plausible C3 carbonyl route into central metabolites (Ricardo et al., 2004; Ritson & Sutherland, 2012).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_010\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface oxidative assembly of pyruvate from glyceraldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_021\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_010\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"TiO2/phosphate minerals\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"UV photoredox; phosphate-assisted carbonyl chemistry\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Photochemical oxidation/rearrangement of triose carbonyls under phosphate-rich conditions yields alpha-keto acid functionality, producing pyruvate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"A surface route into pyruvate is required to avoid overreliance on hydrothermal pyruvate alone. Pyruvate and related alpha-keto acids arise in cyanosulfidic and photochemical carbonyl networks, though exact route details remain system-dependent; this step is included as a moderate-confidence surface feeder (Patel et al., 2015; Muchowska et al., 2020).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_011\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface cyanohydrin-based assembly of oxaloacetate from pyruvate and HCN\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_021\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_012\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\", \"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"phosphate minerals/montmorillonite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"cyanide-rich evaporitic pools; hydration/hydrolysis sequence\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Pyruvate forms a cyanohydrin that, upon hydrolysis and partial oxidation-state adjustment, furnishes the C4 alpha-keto dicarboxylate skeleton of oxaloacetate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This route replaces earlier unsupported direct carboxylation schemes with a nitrile-mediated chain-extension logic that is more aligned with prebiotic cyanide chemistry. While not fully settled experimentally for oxaloacetate specifically, cyanohydrin homologation is chemically more credible than the previously criticized pyruvate-to-oxaloacetate shortcut (Eschenmoser, 2007; Muchowska et al., 2020).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_012\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface transamination/reductive amination of oxaloacetate to aspartate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_012\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_011\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_013\", \"mol_010\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\", \"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite/phosphate minerals\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"wet-dry cycles; amino donor recycling\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Aspartate forms by amino transfer or net reductive amination of oxaloacetate, with alanine/pyruvate serving as a plausible amino transfer pair.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Transamination among alpha-keto acids and amino acids is a chemically grounded way to populate amino-acid networks from hydrothermal alanine and surface ketoacids, and is more defensible than earlier ad hoc chain-extension steps (Muchowska et al., 2019; Powner et al., 2020).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_013\",\n      \"name\": \"Biochemical homologation of aspartate/oxaloacetate to 2-oxoglutarate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_013\", \"mol_005\", \"mol_012\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_014\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [\"mineral interfaces\", \"Fe2+-rich aqueous phase\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-360K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Fe2+-rich mineral interface\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"anoxic pool-interface chemistry; iterative carbonyl/carboxyl exchange\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Network-level C1/C4 coupling and oxidative deamination logic converts aspartate/oxaloacetate-derived carbon skeletons into the C5 alpha-keto acid 2-oxoglutarate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Direct prebiotic synthesis of 2-oxoglutarate remains an open problem; this step is explicitly acknowledged as a gap-bridging, moderate-speculation network connection needed to join robust C4 chemistry to the glutamate/proline family. Its inclusion is justified by abiotic protometabolic studies that generate multiple TCA-like intermediates under Fe-mediated conditions, though not always as a single clean transformation (Muchowska et al., 2017; Keller et al., 2014).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_014\",\n      \"name\": \"Biochemical reductive amination of 2-oxoglutarate to glutamate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_014\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_015\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [\"mineral interfaces\", \"Fe2+-rich aqueous phase\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Fe2+-mediated redox interface\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"anoxic; repeated heating/cooling\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Imine formation at the alpha-keto position followed by reduction yields glutamate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Among late-stage steps, reductive amination of alpha-keto acids is chemically plausible and provides the correct biochemical family precursor for proline. This is substantially more realistic than converting pyruvate directly into higher amino acids (Barge et al., 2019; Muchowska et al., 2019).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_015\",\n      \"name\": \"Biochemical dehydration/cyclization of glutamate to pyroglutamate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_015\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_017\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [\"mineral interfaces\", \"drying surfaces\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"320-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"none\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"false\",\n        \"other\": \"wet-dry cycling on mineral surfaces\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Intramolecular condensation of the gamma-carboxyl with the amino group forms the five-membered lactam pyroglutamate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Pyroglutamate is a credible dehydration product of glutamate under prebiotic drying conditions and serves as a realistic branch point within glutamate-family chemistry (Forsythe et al., 2015; Rodriguez-Garcia et al., 2015).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_016\",\n      \"name\": \"Biochemical partial reduction of glutamate to glutamate semialdehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_015\", \"mol_002\", \"mol_021\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_016\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [\"mineral interfaces\", \"Fe2+-phosphate phase\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Fe2+/phosphate-assisted activation\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"anoxic; concentration in pools; activation chemistry required\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Selective activation of one carboxylate followed by reduction furnishes the corresponding semialdehyde.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Selective conversion of glutamate to glutamate semialdehyde is a necessary but challenging prebiotic step. It is retained because the glutamate semialdehyde/P5C/proline manifold is chemically correct for proline family assembly; however, the exact prebiotic activation chemistry remains unresolved and this step should be viewed as constrained speculation rather than an experimentally established one-pot transformation (Keller et al., 2014; Muchowska et al., 2020).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_017\",\n      \"name\": \"Biochemical interconversion of pyroglutamate and P5C\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_017\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_018\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [\"mineral interfaces\", \"Fe2+-rich aqueous phase\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Fe2+-mediated redox interface\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"hydration/dehydration equilibrium; anoxic\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Reductive ring-carbonyl adjustment or hydrolytic ring-state exchange moves the glutamate family between lactam and imine/carboxylate forms, yielding P5C.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Pyroglutamate is not assumed to be the dominant route, but it is a chemically meaningful side branch converging on the same cyclic imine family as glutamate semialdehyde. This branch is moderately speculative yet more chemically interpretable than the previously criticized pyroglutamate shortcut without family context (Forsythe et al., 2015; Muchowska et al., 2020).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_018\",\n      \"name\": \"Biochemical spontaneous cyclization of glutamate semialdehyde to P5C\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_016\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_018\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [\"mineral interfaces\", \"none\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"none\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"intramolecular cyclization in concentrated solution\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"The gamma-semialdehyde condenses intramolecularly with the amino group to form the cyclic imine P5C.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Once glutamate semialdehyde exists, cyclization to P5C is straightforward and chemically well grounded; this is one of the strongest late-stage steps in the target manifold (Nelson & Cox, biochemistry framework; adapted to prebiotic concentrated-solution conditions).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_019\",\n      \"name\": \"Biochemical reduction of P5C to proline\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_018\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_019\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [\"mineral interfaces\", \"Fe2+-rich aqueous phase\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Fe2+/redox-active mineral interface\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"anoxic reduction; geothermal cycling\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Reduction of the cyclic imine in P5C gives pyrrolidine-2-carboxylate, i.e. proline.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Reduction of a cyclic imine to the corresponding saturated amine is chemically reasonable and provides the final closure to proline. The product is shown as L-proline as target nomenclature, but this step itself is not assumed to generate high enantiomeric excess; any L-enrichment would require secondary selection processes (Blackmond, 2010; Bonner, 1991).\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal acetate-pyruvate-glutamate semialdehyde route\",\n      \"description\": \"A vent-first route from CO2 reduction through acetate and hydrothermal pyruvate, then into oxaloacetate, glutamate, P5C, and proline.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\", \"rxn_016\", \"rxn_018\", \"rxn_019\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_015\", \"mol_018\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P2\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal alanine-assisted aspartate route\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal pyruvate is aminated to alanine, which later serves as amino donor to oxaloacetate on the surface before entry into the glutamate/P5C manifold.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\", \"rxn_016\", \"rxn_018\", \"rxn_019\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_015\", \"mol_018\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P3\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface HCN-formamide-formose to pyruvate route\",\n      \"description\": \"A surface-dominated route from HCN through formamide, formaldehyde, glycolaldehyde, glyceraldehyde, and pyruvate before joining the common proline family branch.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\", \"rxn_016\", \"rxn_018\", \"rxn_019\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_020\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P4\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface glycolaldehyde-centered route\",\n      \"description\": \"A shorter surface route using glycolaldehyde as the main carbon hub into glyceraldehyde, pyruvate, and the glutamate branch.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\", \"rxn_016\", \"rxn_018\", \"rxn_019\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_018\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P5\",\n      \"name\": \"Mixed hydrothermal-surface pyruvate convergence route\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal pyruvate and surface HCN converge directly at oxaloacetate via cyanohydrin homologation, then proceed through glutamate semialdehyde.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\", \"rxn_016\", \"rxn_018\", \"rxn_019\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_015\", \"mol_018\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P6\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal formate plus surface C4 assembly route\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal formate is carried into surface and biochemical chemistry as the C1 contributor to the C4-to-C5 expansion that gives 2-oxoglutarate and then proline.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\", \"rxn_016\", \"rxn_018\", \"rxn_019\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_014\", \"mol_015\", \"mol_018\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P7\",\n      \"name\": \"Pyroglutamate branch from glutamate\",\n      \"description\": \"After glutamate formation, wet-dry cycling diverts material through pyroglutamate before convergence on P5C and proline.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\", \"rxn_015\", \"rxn_017\", \"rxn_019\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_015\", \"mol_017\", \"mol_018\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P8\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal glutamate-to-pyroglutamate route\",\n      \"description\": \"Vent-fixed carbon flows through hydrothermal pyruvate into the glutamate family, then uses the pyroglutamate side branch rather than semialdehyde-first closure.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\", \"rxn_015\", \"rxn_017\", \"rxn_019\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_015\", \"mol_017\", \"mol_018\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P9\",\n      \"name\": \"Alanine-mediated mixed-environment route with semialdehyde closure\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal alanine is explicitly used as amino-transfer currency to populate aspartate and ultimately glutamate, followed by semialdehyde cyclization.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\", \"rxn_016\", \"rxn_018\", \"rxn_019\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_015\", \"mol_016\", \"mol_018\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P10\",\n      \"name\": \"Maximum-convergence network route\",\n      \"description\": \"A redundancy-rich path that samples both surface carbonyl buildup and hydrothermal fixed-carbon inputs before entering the common glutamate/P5C manifold.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\", \"rxn_015\", \"rxn_017\", \"rxn_019\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_015\", \"mol_018\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"hub_molecules\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_015\", \"mol_018\"],\n  \"convergence_points\": [\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_010\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_004\", \"rxn_011\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_012\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_011\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_015\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_014\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_015\", \"rxn_016\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_018\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_017\", \"rxn_018\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_019\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_004\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_005\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_006\", \"rxn_011\"]\n    }\n  ]\n}", "parsed_response": {"target_molecule": "L-Proline", "overall_strategy": "This network targets proline through a chemically conservative prebiotic family centered on glutamate-semialdehyde / 1-pyrroline-5-carboxylate (P5C), while avoiding poorly supported shortcuts criticized in prior attempts. Hydrothermal chemistry supplies robust C1-C3 feedstocks (formate, acetate, pyruvate, alanine) from CO2/H2 on iron-sulfur minerals. Surface chemistry supplies HCN, formaldehyde, glycolaldehyde, glyceraldehyde, oxaloacetate, aspartate, and glutamate via cyanosulfidic photochemistry, borate-stabilized sugar chemistry, and Strecker/transamination-like sequences under wet-dry cycling. Biochemical/prebiotic closure then converts glutamate to glutamate semialdehyde, cyclizes to P5C, and reduces to proline; stereochemical enrichment to L-proline is not assumed at the synthetic step itself but is attributed to downstream mineral or chiral-phase selection. The network is organized around hubs HCN, pyruvate, oxaloacetate, glutamate, and P5C, with multiple convergent routes from hydrothermal and surface environments into the proline family.", "molecules": [{"id": "mol_001", "formula": "CO2", "iupac_name": "carbon dioxide", "common_name": "carbon dioxide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_002", "formula": "H2", "iupac_name": "molecular hydrogen", "common_name": "hydrogen", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2/h1H", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_003", "formula": "NH3", "iupac_name": "azane", "common_name": "ammonia", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_004", "formula": "HCN", "iupac_name": "hydrogen cyanide", "common_name": "hydrogen cyanide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_005", "formula": "CH2O2", "iupac_name": "methanoic acid", "common_name": "formic acid/formate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH2O2/c2-1-3/h1H,(H,2,3)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_006", "formula": "C2H4O2", "iupac_name": "ethanoic acid", "common_name": "acetic acid/acetate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H4O2/c1-2(3)4/h1H3,(H,3,4)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_007", "formula": "CH2O", "iupac_name": "methanal", "common_name": "formaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH2O/c1-2/h1H2", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_008", "formula": "C2H4O2", "iupac_name": "2-hydroxyethanal", "common_name": "glycolaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H4O2/c3-1-2-4/h1,3H,2H2", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_009", "formula": "C3H6O3", "iupac_name": "2,3-dihydroxypropanal", "common_name": "glyceraldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H6O3/c4-1-3(6)2-5/h1,3,5-6H,2H2", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_010", "formula": "C3H4O3", "iupac_name": "2-oxopropanoic acid", "common_name": "pyruvic acid/pyruvate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H4O3/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h1H3,(H,5,6)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_011", "formula": "C3H7NO2", "iupac_name": "2-aminopropanoic acid", "common_name": "alanine", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H7NO2/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h2H,4H2,1H3,(H,5,6)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_012", "formula": "C4H4O5", "iupac_name": "2-oxobutanedioic acid", "common_name": "oxaloacetic acid/oxaloacetate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C4H4O5/c5-2(4(8)9)1-3(6)7/h1H2,(H,6,7)(H,8,9)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_013", "formula": "C4H7NO4", "iupac_name": "2-aminobutanedioic acid", "common_name": "aspartic acid/aspartate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C4H7NO4/c5-2(4(8)9)1-3(6)7/h2H,1,5H2,(H,6,7)(H,8,9)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_014", "formula": "C5H6O5", "iupac_name": "2-oxopentanedioic acid", "common_name": "alpha-ketoglutaric acid/2-oxoglutarate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H6O5/c6-3(5(9)10)1-2-4(7)8/h1-2H2,(H,7,8)(H,9,10)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_015", "formula": "C5H9NO4", "iupac_name": "2-aminopentanedioic acid", "common_name": "glutamic acid/glutamate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H9NO4/c6-3(5(9)10)1-2-4(7)8/h3H,1-2,6H2,(H,7,8)(H,9,10)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_016", "formula": "C5H9NO3", "iupac_name": "5-amino-4-oxopentanoic acid", "common_name": "glutamate semialdehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H9NO3/c6-3-1-2-4(7)5(8)9/h2-3,6H2,1H2,(H,8,9)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_017", "formula": "C5H7NO2", "iupac_name": "5-oxopyrrolidine-2-carboxylic acid", "common_name": "pyroglutamic acid", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H7NO3/c7-4-1-2-6-3(4)5(8)9/h3,6H,1-2H2,(H,8,9)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_018", "formula": "C5H7NO2", "iupac_name": "3,4-dihydro-2H-pyrrole-2-carboxylic acid", "common_name": "1-pyrroline-5-carboxylic acid", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H7NO2/c7-5(8)4-2-1-3-6-4/h4H,1-3H2,(H,7,8)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_019", "formula": "C5H9NO2", "iupac_name": "(2S)-pyrrolidine-2-carboxylic acid", "common_name": "L-proline", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H9NO2/c7-5(8)4-2-1-3-6-4/h4,6H,1-3H2,(H,7,8)/t4-/m0/s1", "role": "target", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_020", "formula": "CH3NO", "iupac_name": "formamide", "common_name": "formamide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH3NO/c2-1-3/h1H,(H2,2,3)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_021", "formula": "H3PO4", "iupac_name": "phosphoric acid", "common_name": "phosphate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H3O4P/c1-5(2,3)4/h(H3,1,2,3,4)", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}], "reactions": [{"id": "rxn_001", "name": "Hydrothermal CO2 reduction to formate", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_005"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite (Fe3S4)", "mackinawite (FeS)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "greigite/mackinawite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "alkaline vent conditions; anoxic; H2-rich"}, "mechanism": "Mineral-surface hydrogenation of CO2 to surface-bound formyl/formate equivalents followed by release as formate.", "reasoning": "Reduction of CO2 to formate on iron-sulfur minerals under alkaline hydrothermal conditions is among the best-supported vent reactions and provides a defensible C1 entry point for the network (He et al., 2010; Preiner et al., 2020)."}, {"id": "rxn_002", "name": "Hydrothermal reduction of CO2/formate to acetate", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002", "mol_005"], "outputs": ["mol_006"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite (Fe3S4)", "magnetite (Fe3O4)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-450K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "greigite/magnetite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "alkaline vent microcompartments; anoxic"}, "mechanism": "Sequential C1 reduction and C-C coupling on Fe-S/oxide surfaces produces acetyl-like species hydrolyzing to acetate.", "reasoning": "Acetate formation from CO2/H2 in hydrothermal systems is consistent with acetyl-CoA-analog vent chemistry and Fe-mineral-catalyzed carbon fixation (Huber & Wachtershauser, 1997; Preiner et al., 2020)."}, {"id": "rxn_003", "name": "Hydrothermal pyruvate synthesis from CO2-derived carbon", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002", "mol_006"], "outputs": ["mol_010"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite (Fe3O4)", "greigite (Fe3S4)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "magnetite/greigite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "anoxic; vent pH gradients; reductive carboxylation-like mineral chemistry"}, "mechanism": "Acetyl-like carbon is further carboxylated/oxidized on mixed Fe oxide-sulfide surfaces to generate alpha-keto acid character, yielding pyruvate.", "reasoning": "Pyruvate generation in abiotic hydrothermal simulations is less secure than formate/acetate but has experimental and systems-level support in Fe-catalyzed CO2 fixation networks; retained here as a moderate-confidence hydrothermal feeder rather than the sole route (Cody et al., 2000; Varma et al., 2018)."}, {"id": "rxn_004", "name": "Hydrothermal reductive amination of pyruvate to alanine", "inputs": ["mol_010", "mol_003", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_011"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["pyrite (FeS2)", "greigite (Fe3S4)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "pyrite/greigite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "anoxic; NH3-bearing vent fluids"}, "mechanism": "Imine formation from pyruvate and ammonia followed by mineral-assisted reduction yields alanine.", "reasoning": "Reductive amination of alpha-keto acids on mineral surfaces is a plausible vent process and alanine provides a realistic amino donor for later transamination chemistry (Barge et al., 2019; Muchowska et al., 2019)."}, {"id": "rxn_005", "name": "Surface UV-cyanosulfidic generation of HCN from simple C/N feedstocks", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_004"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "sulfide minerals (molybdenite/stibnite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-340K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "TiO2 and sulfide minerals", "aqueous": "true", "other": "UV irradiation; anoxic shallow pools; photoredox sulfur chemistry"}, "mechanism": "Photochemical redox cycling in sulfur-bearing surface settings generates reduced nitrile carbon, furnishing HCN as a cyanosulfidic reservoir species.", "reasoning": "Rather than deriving HCN from formaldehyde plus ammonia, this network places HCN in a more defensible cyanosulfidic photochemical context consistent with surface prebiotic chemistry (Patel et al., 2015; Xu et al., 2018)."}, {"id": "rxn_006", "name": "Surface hydrolysis of HCN to formamide", "inputs": ["mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_020"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "montmorillonite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "TiO2/montmorillonite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "UV-assisted hydrolysis in evaporitic pools"}, "mechanism": "Partial hydration of nitrile carbon converts HCN into amide carbonyl functionality, yielding formamide.", "reasoning": "Formamide is a recognized prebiotic reservoir deriving from cyanide hydrolysis and links nitrile chemistry to broader surface photochemistry (Saladino et al., 2012; Ferus et al., 2017)."}, {"id": "rxn_007", "name": "Surface photochemical conversion of formamide to formaldehyde reservoir", "inputs": ["mol_020"], "outputs": ["mol_007"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-340K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "TiO2 with phosphate-rich mineral surfaces", "aqueous": "true", "other": "UV irradiation; shallow film chemistry"}, "mechanism": "Photochemical fragmentation and hydrolysis of C1 amide reservoirs furnish reactive carbonyl species including formaldehyde.", "reasoning": "This step is included as a conservative C1 carbonyl source from surface nitrogen-carbon reservoirs; while indirect and context-dependent, formamide photochemistry is experimentally linked to diverse reduced carbon products. This step is somewhat speculative but more defensible than the previously criticized direct formate-to-formaldehyde hydrothermal step (Saladino et al., 2012; Ferus et al., 2017)."}, {"id": "rxn_008", "name": "Surface formose entry to glycolaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_007"], "outputs": ["mol_008"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)", "TiO2 (anatase/rutile)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-340K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "borate minerals", "aqueous": "true", "other": "evaporitic concentration; borate stabilization of sugars"}, "mechanism": "Formaldehyde undergoes base/mineral-mediated C-C coupling to the C2 sugar aldehyde, with borate suppressing destructive side reactions.", "reasoning": "Glycolaldehyde is a central prebiotic sugar precursor accessible from formaldehyde chemistry, especially in borate-containing settings that stabilize carbohydrate intermediates (Ricardo et al., 2004; Ritson & Sutherland, 2012)."}, {"id": "rxn_009", "name": "Surface aldol extension of glycolaldehyde to glyceraldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_008", "mol_007"], "outputs": ["mol_009"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)", "montmorillonite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-340K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "borate minerals/montmorillonite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "wet-dry cycling; sugar stabilization"}, "mechanism": "Aldol addition between C1 and C2 aldehydes generates the C3 triose glyceraldehyde.", "reasoning": "Aldol growth from glycolaldehyde to glyceraldehyde is a standard element of prebiotic sugar chemistry and provides a plausible C3 carbonyl route into central metabolites (Ricardo et al., 2004; Ritson & Sutherland, 2012)."}, {"id": "rxn_010", "name": "Surface oxidative assembly of pyruvate from glyceraldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_009", "mol_021"], "outputs": ["mol_010"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-340K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "TiO2/phosphate minerals", "aqueous": "true", "other": "UV photoredox; phosphate-assisted carbonyl chemistry"}, "mechanism": "Photochemical oxidation/rearrangement of triose carbonyls under phosphate-rich conditions yields alpha-keto acid functionality, producing pyruvate.", "reasoning": "A surface route into pyruvate is required to avoid overreliance on hydrothermal pyruvate alone. Pyruvate and related alpha-keto acids arise in cyanosulfidic and photochemical carbonyl networks, though exact route details remain system-dependent; this step is included as a moderate-confidence surface feeder (Patel et al., 2015; Muchowska et al., 2020)."}, {"id": "rxn_011", "name": "Surface cyanohydrin-based assembly of oxaloacetate from pyruvate and HCN", "inputs": ["mol_010", "mol_004", "mol_021"], "outputs": ["mol_012"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)", "montmorillonite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "phosphate minerals/montmorillonite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "cyanide-rich evaporitic pools; hydration/hydrolysis sequence"}, "mechanism": "Pyruvate forms a cyanohydrin that, upon hydrolysis and partial oxidation-state adjustment, furnishes the C4 alpha-keto dicarboxylate skeleton of oxaloacetate.", "reasoning": "This route replaces earlier unsupported direct carboxylation schemes with a nitrile-mediated chain-extension logic that is more aligned with prebiotic cyanide chemistry. While not fully settled experimentally for oxaloacetate specifically, cyanohydrin homologation is chemically more credible than the previously criticized pyruvate-to-oxaloacetate shortcut (Eschenmoser, 2007; Muchowska et al., 2020)."}, {"id": "rxn_012", "name": "Surface transamination/reductive amination of oxaloacetate to aspartate", "inputs": ["mol_012", "mol_003", "mol_011"], "outputs": ["mol_013", "mol_010"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite", "phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-340K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite/phosphate minerals", "aqueous": "true", "other": "wet-dry cycles; amino donor recycling"}, "mechanism": "Aspartate forms by amino transfer or net reductive amination of oxaloacetate, with alanine/pyruvate serving as a plausible amino transfer pair.", "reasoning": "Transamination among alpha-keto acids and amino acids is a chemically grounded way to populate amino-acid networks from hydrothermal alanine and surface ketoacids, and is more defensible than earlier ad hoc chain-extension steps (Muchowska et al., 2019; Powner et al., 2020)."}, {"id": "rxn_013", "name": "Biochemical homologation of aspartate/oxaloacetate to 2-oxoglutarate", "inputs": ["mol_013", "mol_005", "mol_012"], "outputs": ["mol_014"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": ["mineral interfaces", "Fe2+-rich aqueous phase"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-360K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "Fe2+-rich mineral interface", "aqueous": "true", "other": "anoxic pool-interface chemistry; iterative carbonyl/carboxyl exchange"}, "mechanism": "Network-level C1/C4 coupling and oxidative deamination logic converts aspartate/oxaloacetate-derived carbon skeletons into the C5 alpha-keto acid 2-oxoglutarate.", "reasoning": "Direct prebiotic synthesis of 2-oxoglutarate remains an open problem; this step is explicitly acknowledged as a gap-bridging, moderate-speculation network connection needed to join robust C4 chemistry to the glutamate/proline family. Its inclusion is justified by abiotic protometabolic studies that generate multiple TCA-like intermediates under Fe-mediated conditions, though not always as a single clean transformation (Muchowska et al., 2017; Keller et al., 2014)."}, {"id": "rxn_014", "name": "Biochemical reductive amination of 2-oxoglutarate to glutamate", "inputs": ["mol_014", "mol_003", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_015"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": ["mineral interfaces", "Fe2+-rich aqueous phase"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "Fe2+-mediated redox interface", "aqueous": "true", "other": "anoxic; repeated heating/cooling"}, "mechanism": "Imine formation at the alpha-keto position followed by reduction yields glutamate.", "reasoning": "Among late-stage steps, reductive amination of alpha-keto acids is chemically plausible and provides the correct biochemical family precursor for proline. This is substantially more realistic than converting pyruvate directly into higher amino acids (Barge et al., 2019; Muchowska et al., 2019)."}, {"id": "rxn_015", "name": "Biochemical dehydration/cyclization of glutamate to pyroglutamate", "inputs": ["mol_015"], "outputs": ["mol_017"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": ["mineral interfaces", "drying surfaces"], "conditions": {"temperature": "320-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "none", "aqueous": "false", "other": "wet-dry cycling on mineral surfaces"}, "mechanism": "Intramolecular condensation of the gamma-carboxyl with the amino group forms the five-membered lactam pyroglutamate.", "reasoning": "Pyroglutamate is a credible dehydration product of glutamate under prebiotic drying conditions and serves as a realistic branch point within glutamate-family chemistry (Forsythe et al., 2015; Rodriguez-Garcia et al., 2015)."}, {"id": "rxn_016", "name": "Biochemical partial reduction of glutamate to glutamate semialdehyde", "inputs": ["mol_015", "mol_002", "mol_021"], "outputs": ["mol_016"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": ["mineral interfaces", "Fe2+-phosphate phase"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "Fe2+/phosphate-assisted activation", "aqueous": "true", "other": "anoxic; concentration in pools; activation chemistry required"}, "mechanism": "Selective activation of one carboxylate followed by reduction furnishes the corresponding semialdehyde.", "reasoning": "Selective conversion of glutamate to glutamate semialdehyde is a necessary but challenging prebiotic step. It is retained because the glutamate semialdehyde/P5C/proline manifold is chemically correct for proline family assembly; however, the exact prebiotic activation chemistry remains unresolved and this step should be viewed as constrained speculation rather than an experimentally established one-pot transformation (Keller et al., 2014; Muchowska et al., 2020)."}, {"id": "rxn_017", "name": "Biochemical interconversion of pyroglutamate and P5C", "inputs": ["mol_017", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_018"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": ["mineral interfaces", "Fe2+-rich aqueous phase"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "Fe2+-mediated redox interface", "aqueous": "true", "other": "hydration/dehydration equilibrium; anoxic"}, "mechanism": "Reductive ring-carbonyl adjustment or hydrolytic ring-state exchange moves the glutamate family between lactam and imine/c